<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni, Moi Call for Peace in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
and his Kenyan counterpart Daniel Arap Moi called for all African
countries suffering internal strife to try to restore peace and
stability to their countries.
</P>
<P>
They made this call in a joint communique released here
Thursday afternoon following Moi's three-day state visit to
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the two leaders held extensive discussions
on the peace and security in Africa with special emphasis on that
of the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
They expressed strong support for the efforts by countries of
the region to try and find lasting peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
On Burundi, the two heads of state underscored the need for
the Buyoya regime to make tangible progress on the all-party
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the developments in other parts of Africa, they
encouraged on-going efforts aimed at bringing about total peace
and security in Africa so that the continent can use its rich
resources for socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
They also hailed the restoration of democratic rule in Liberia
and Sierra Leone and called for progress in finding solutions to
the conflicts in Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
