<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 16:00 GMT, May 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- A high-ranking Indian official said Thursday that
India wants to continue dialogue and improve relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Brajesh Mishra, principal secretary of Indian Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee, said to reporters that both sides should put
aside the statements made against each other over the past few
days and restart the dialogue. (BC-India-China-Dialogue)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Leader of the Palestinian Islamic Resistance
Movement Hamas Sheikh Ahmed Yassin started on Thursday a three-day
visit to Syria in an effort to unify the Palestinian groups based
here.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Yassin is expected to hold talks with
Syrian leaders on the latest developments in the Middle East, and
Hamas' attitude toward the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
and the Oslo accords. (BC-Syria-Hamas-Leader)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Afghanistan's Taliban militia Thursday urged the
United Nations to be impartial in mediating peace talks among
warring factions, saying otherwise the world body can "hardly play
any effective role" in resolving the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the U.N. proves its impartiality ... it can hardly play
any effective role as mediator, and gain any achievement in
resolving Afghan issues," Taliban's envoy in Pakistan Adul Hakim
Mujahid told reporters here Thursday afternoon.
(BC-Pakistan-Afghanistan-UN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia's new President Bacharuddib Jusuf Habibie
pledged here on Thursday evening to speed up reforms in all fields
and to form an honest government as early as possible to meet the
aspiration of the people.
</P>
<P>
In a nation-wide television address, Habibie said he needs
support from the whole nation to carry out his duties in
implementing political, economic and legal reforms at the current
difficult time when the country is facing severe political and
economic crisis. (BC-Indonesia-Habibie-Reforms) 
</P>
