<HEADLINE> Russia Resists U.S. Pressure on Cooperation With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Congress is in no position
to exert political pressure on Russia regarding its cooperation
with Iran, said Yeltsin's Press Secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress intends to debate a bill on sanctions against
Moscow, claiming that Russia provided Iran with nuclear
technology, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Russia adheres to the principles of non-proliferation regarding
nuclear weapons and nuclear technology in its cooperation with
Iran, said Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
Moscow will never bow to political pressure from the
U.S. Congress on this matter, the press secretary stressed.
</P>
<P>
It is totally baseless to assume that cooperation between
Russia and Iran on nuclear energy will present dangers. And Russia
would not like to see its companies squeezed out of the world
markets by unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
Russia does not wish to see its neighbors become new members of
the so-called "nuclear club" or possess nuclear potential, said
the Kremlin official.
</P>
<P>
Under a contract worth 800 million U.S. dollars, Russian
experts are helping Iran build a nuclear power plant in Bushire,
which has drawn criticism from the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
