<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Unions Welcomes Talks with Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) Thursday said it welcomes dialog with President
Robert Mugabe to iron out differences between the organization
and the government.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU second Vice-President Shangwa Chifamba said workers'
representatives wished to meet the president as soon as possible
and resolve all differences which have resulted in labor unrest
over the past six months, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the ZCTU had sent the letter to Mugabe through Public
Service, Labor and Social Welfare Minister Florence Chitauro
requesting the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The workers have been demanding that the government scrap the
two-and-half percent increase in sales tax which was introduced
last year, the new 15 percent tax on pension profits and the five
percent development levy.
</P>
<P>
Last December and this March, the ZCTU organized the national
job stayaways to protest prices and tax hikes and on May Day, it
threatened that a longer job stayaway was looming if the
government did not heed its requests.
</P>
<P>
Chifamba said, "we are now waiting for a date to be set to
meet the president. We hope the meeting will not be too long
because it might be overtaken by events."
</P>
<P>
"The ZCTU welcomes this opening of dialog with the government
because we are searching for solutions to the problems," he said,
adding that further job stayaways would only be used as a last
resort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
