<HEADLINE> French Gov't Appoints Expert on Int'l Financial Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
Thursday appointed an economist as a government expert on
international financial markets to study ways to reduce risks from
these markets.
</P>
<P>
Olivier Davanne, who is an advisor of Minister of Employment
and Solidarity Martine Aubry, will submit a report on the causes
of instability in the international financial markets and
"foreseeable progress" for reducing or avoiding monetary and
financial crises.
</P>
<P>
The 39-year-old economist is specialized in macro-economy, and
has worked in the Goldman Sachs Investment Bank as its co-director
of research on European economy.
</P>
<P>
After the financial crisis struck Asia in the latter half of
1997, the French government is more and more concerned about the
international financial speculators.
</P>
<P>
But Minister of Finance and Economy Dominique Strauss-Kahn has
ruled out a Communist proposal to impose taxes on international
capitals withdrawing from France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
