<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana GDP Grows by 7% in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Botswana recorded seven
percent growth in gross domestic product (GDP) for the year
ending June, 1997, which remained the same as in the previous
year, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate fell short of government expectations of over
seven percent.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Botswana governor Baledzi Gaolathe said in a
preliminary presentation Wednesday that growth had been
broad-based, but led by a 7.5 percent improvement in the
non-mining sector, South African Press Association reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Figures released before showed that the country's GDP stood at
18,051 million Pula (4,513 million U.S. Dollars) in the 1996/97
financial year, compared with the 14,631 million Pula (3,658
million Dollars) in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, Botswana's exports rose by 37 percent,
improving the balance of payments to 2,400 million Pula (600
million Dollars) against 1,650 million (412.5 million Dollars) in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The country's international reserves rose 13 percent to 21,600
million Pula (5,400 million Dollars) from 19,100 million Pula
(4,775 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the central bank reported a 40 percent growth rate
in its earnings for the year ending December, 1997, from 1,077
million Pula (269.3 million Dollars) in 1996 to 1,475 million
Pula (368.8 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The detailed annual report is expected within two weeks, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
