<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Warns of New Violence if </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official on
Thursday urged the United States to pressure Israel to accept its
proposal on Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank and warned of
violence if U.S. efforts fail.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief peace negotiator Saeb Erekat called on
Washington not to allow Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
to postpone again a decision on the U.S. proposal demanding Israel
to withdraw from another 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks as U.S. President Bill Clinton was expected
to meet with top foreign policy advisors to discuss Washington's
next steps in breaking the impasse of the peace talks between the
Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Erekat, also minister of Local Government of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA), expressed hope that Washington would
soon go public with its plan and press Israel to accept it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ahmed Tibi, senior advisor to PNA President Yasser
Arafat, told Israel Radio that if Israel continues to reject the
U.S. proposal and as a result the peace process dies, "widespread
violence" could erupt in the region.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has accepted the U.S. proposal, but Israel has not.
Citing security concerns, Netanyahu has said Israel will hand over
no more than 9 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Yediot Ahronoth daily reported on Thursday that the
U.S. has given Netanyahu a one-week ultimatum to accept the
U.S. proposal or to be blamed publicly for the failure in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has denied the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
