<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Consider Whether to Hold Mideast Peace Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
said Thursday that European Union foreign ministers will consider
next Monday whether there is a need to launch a new international
conference in a bid to restart the the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The proposal about a Middle East peace conference was floated
by French President Jacques Chirac and his Egyptian counterpart,
Hosni Mubarak, during their meeting in Paris Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference after talks with visiting
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa in Bonn, Kinkel said that EU
foreign ministers will discuss the proposal at their regular
meeting next Monday in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
"Given the current standstill in the Middle East peace process,
we must consider what we can do to get out of the crisis," Kinkel
said. However he also noted that a new peace conference was only
one of the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also stressed that the United States should remain as
"the main sponsor of Middle East peace" though it appeared now
necessary for the EU to play a stronger role.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concern about the failure of the latest peace
initiative launched by Washington, Moussa said that the Middle
East peace "has not only reached a standstill, it has also reached
a major crisis point."
</P>
<P>
He also sharply criticized Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu for rejecting all peace proposals and called on the
international community to increase pressure on the Israeli
leader.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in the Middle East is not a regional issue. It
is linked to international peace and security. Therefore, it is up
to us all to stand firm against the policy followed by the Israeli
government," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
