<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP Urged to Do More in Fresh Water Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese delegation Thursday
urged the U. N. Environment Program (UNEP) to play a more active
role in the management of global fresh water resources and make
greater contributions to the protection of these resources.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the on-going fifth special session of the UNEP
Governing Council, a Chinese official proposed that an expert
group be established to study the situation of environmental
management of fresh water resources in the world.
</P>
<P>
The group should put forward policy framework and
methodologies for environmentally sound management of fresh
water, the official of the Chinese delegation added.
</P>
<P>
He said at the three-day meeting which opened Wednesday that
UNEP should assist the developing countries in strengthening
their capacity for fresh water management, especially in the
field of getting access to the practicable technologies.
</P>
<P>
The issue of fresh water is among the four main issues being
discussed at the special session in order to implement the
Nairobi Declaration adopted last year at the 19th session of the
UNEP Governing Council.
</P>
<P>
At the opening meeting, UNEP Executive Director Klaus Topfer
noted that "supply of fresh water would be a critical issue in
the years to come."
</P>
<P>
He announced that recently the Global Environment Fund (GEF)
had approved a Global International Waters Assessment which would
provide governments, the GEF and UNEP with information on Major
water issues.
</P>
<P>
UNEP is also exploring the possibility of developing a global
action program focusing on the environmental aspects of fresh
water management, the UNEP chief added.
</P>
<P>
During the discussions, the Group of 77 and China Thursday
urged UNEP to play a vital role in the sustainable development of
fresh water.
</P>
<P>
They noted that it was necessary to transfer applied
technology and related know-hows to the developing countries for
the sustainable development and management of fresh water
resources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they urged UNEP executive director to take steps to
help the developing countries in collecting, interpreting and
disseminating information for water management decisions.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, the European Union also requested the
executive director in collaboration with other U.N. bodies, to
provide advice in support of national policies for integrated
water management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
