<HEADLINE> Retired French Officer Expelled by Central African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A retired French army officer was
expelled by the government of the Central African Republic after
being detained for 15 days, because he was accused of threatening
the state security of the country.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported from Bangui that
Lieutenant-Colonel Michel-Paul Audigier was immediately arrested
on arriving at the Mpoko airport of Bangui on May 6.
</P>
<P>
Police said that Audigier was carrying a map of the airport
with "indications on the sensitive points of the site," but they
did not give further details on how he was threatening state
security.
</P>
<P>
He was questioned for several days by police before being
presented to President Ange-Felix Patasse himself. He was then
ordered to leave the country on the first plane available by the
interior minister.
</P>
<P>
AFP said that Audigier was arrested probably because he was
suspected to be a mercenary.
</P>
<P>
Patasse said in an interview with the French daily Liberation
in March that mercenaries were being recruited in France and
Belgium to overthrow him.
</P>
<P>
"France, nostalgic of its past... wants to keep its colonial
stronghold at any price," said Patasse.
</P>
<P>
France has withdrawn its 1,400 troops from two military bases
in the Central African Republic, in the wake of a series of
mutinies by soldiers opposing Patasse last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
