<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Meets World Bank President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin met
with World Bank President James Wolfensohn here Thursday to
discuss with him support for the efforts of the Russian government
and Central Bank, according to Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Yeltsin said that after six year's cooperation
with the World Bank, Russia has proved to be a reliable partner
and hopes to continue cooperation with the bank in future.
</P>
<P>
Deputy head of the Russian president's office Alexander
Livshits, who attended the meeting, quoted Wolfensohn as saying
that the World Bank backs actions by the new Russian government
and wishes that the Russian market should also back these actions.
</P>
<P>
Livshits told a briefing that the bank's president supports the
latest steps by the Russian government and the Central Bank to
normalize the situation on the financial market.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko Thursday also met with
Wolfensohn and discussed with him a program for Russia's
borrowings from the World Bank this year and ways of implementing
it.
</P>
<P>
The two sides focused on loans for social reforms, especially
for pension security in Russia, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko meanwhile requested a loan for upgrading the coal
industry as part of a second "coal" loan he had tried to arrange
through the World Bank as a Fuel and Energy Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with State Duma deputies on the day, the head of the
World Bank said that discussion on World Bank financing for Russia
is impossible until the country has settled its social problems.
However, the bank is ready to continue to cooperate with Russia,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn said that he believes in Russia and, after his
meeting with the Russian president and prime minister, he saw that
they are ready to combat the economic difficulties facing the
country.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is ready to be a long-term partner of Russia and
appreciates the country's readiness to cooperates facing the
country, the president of the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
