<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs U.S. Ratification for Expanding NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Thursday gave formal U.S. approval for expanding the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) to include Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
At a White House ceremony, Clinton signed the instrument of
ratification passed by the Senate on April 30.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to help to build a Europe that is undivided, free,
democratic, at peace and secure," Clinton said before putting his
signature to the document.
</P>
<P>
A larger NATO, Clinton said, will mean American troops "will be
much less likely to cross the Atlantic to fight and die in a war."
</P>
<P>
For the 60 million people in Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic, NATO membership means they can "know that what they
build in peace they will be able to keep in security," he added.
</P>
<P>
Amendment to the treaty, which was signed on April 4, 1949,
creating NATO, will have to be ratified by all the current 16
members.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the U.S., Canada, Denmark, Germany and Norway
have ratified the eastward NATO expansion. It is the first
enlargement of the alliance since Spain joined in 1982.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders are expected to convene a summit in Washington
next April to formally welcome the three new members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
