<HEADLINE> 50,000 "Street Kids" Recorded in Moldovan Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The number of fugitive and
homeless children, the so-called "street kids," reached a record
50,000 in the Moldovan capital Chisinau, reported the Moldovan
news agency BASA-Press Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Many underage children have to beg or quit school because of
miserable conditions in their families, said Nelli Berezovschi,
head of the city hall's family and child protection direction.
Over 900 pupils have left the school, while the number of
abandoned children is on the rise, he added.
</P>
<P>
A total of 430 minors were caught in offenses last year, but
only 10 of them were under police supervision because of their
predisposition to crime, Berezovschi said.
</P>
<P>
The municipal fund of social protection allocated in 1997 was
some 1.7 million lei (about 360,000 U.S. dollars) in material
assistance for 6,136 families with three and more children under
18.
</P>
<P>
Joanna Rogers, managerial director of the European Children
Trust for Bulgaria, Romania and Moldova, said Wednesday during an
international seminar in Chisinau that the grave condition of
"street kids" confirms the need to introduce new, more efficient
forms of support in poor families.
</P>
<P>
The European Children Trust held on May 20-21 -- as part of a
trial project -- a seminar with the theme of "principles and
methodology of temporary protection in a family." The seminar
aimed at developing services for children in risky conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
