<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt-Germany trade volume in 1997 stood at about 3.8
billion Germany marks (about 2.13 billion U.S. dollars), 900
million marks (504.2 million dollars) more than that in 1996, the
Egyptian Al-Ahram daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili said that
Egypt exported 468.3 million marks (263.35 million dollars) worth
of goods in the year, increasing by 14.4 million marks (8.07
million dollars) from the 1996 level.
</P>
<P>
Exports of cotton yarn and textiles rose to 147.3 million marks
(82.52 million dollars) from 112.9 million marks (63.25 million
dollars) in 1996, accounting for 31.45 percent of Egypt's exports
to Germany in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The value of German exports to Egypt was at 3.3 billion marks
(1.85 billion dollars) in 1997, the Egyptian minister said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Agriculture Youssef Wali has said that Egypt and the European
Union (EU) have reached in principle a trade agreement, the
Egyptian newspaper Al-Alam El-Youm reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Egypt will export to the EU 500,000 tonnes
of potatoes each year.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen will buy from Britain a ship for combatting
maritime pollution under an agreement signed here on Thursday
between the Yemeni General Authority of Maritime Affairs and the
British Corporation for Ships Helmatic.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the ship stands at 38 million Yemeni riyals (more
than 280,000 dollars), which will be financed by the Yemeni
General Authority of Maritime Affairs, the Yemeni News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The ship will be used to patrol Yemen's territorial waters and
supervise pollution in the sea.
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni agency has planned to buy two more ships of the
kind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
