<HEADLINE> Russian Mideast Envoy Pessimistic About Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 21 (Xinhua) -- After a shuttle visit to the Middle
East region, Russian special peace envoy Victor Possevalyuk
Thursday said he was pessimistic about the current peace process
in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The general impression I have got from the visit intends to
be pessimistic as the situation is quite complicated,"
Possevalyuk said at a news conference following his meeting with
Lebanese Foreign Minister Fares Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
During his Middle East tour, the Russian envoy has visited
Egypt, Palestinian self-rule areas, Israel, Jordan, Syria and
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestinian track in the peace process has remained
in a stalemate while there has been no change on the Syrian and
Lebanese track.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret about the outcome of the United States
efforts to advance the peace process which has been stalled since
March 1997.
</P>
<P>
The United States has so far failed to persuade Israel to
accept its proposal to hand over a 13.1 percent land of the West
Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Lebanese track has been deadlocked since the
hardline Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu came to power
in June, 1996.
</P>
<P>
But, Possevalyuk stressed that Russia would play an active
role in the next stage of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Israeli proposal of withdrawal from south Lebanon, he said
that he had repeatedly stressed during his visit that the special
relations between Lebanon and Syria must be taken into
consideration.
</P>
<P>
Israel has suggested that it would withdraw its troops from
south Lebanon if the Lebanese government agrees to provide
security guarantee.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria rejected the offer, saying that the
withdrawal must be unconditional as stipulated in the United
Nations Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also insisted that their negotiations with
Israel must be held simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has some 40,000 troops in Lebanon, seeks a
comprehensive solution which will involve an Israeli withdrawal
from the Golan Heights, captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle
East war.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
areas from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Possevalyuk arrived here from Damascus Thursday morning and
has left for home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
