<HEADLINE> Mauritius Keen to Engage in Mozambique's SEZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Mauritius is keen to participate in
developing a special economic zone (SEZ) in the Valley of Zambeze
of the central Mozambique, Mauritian Minister of Economic
Development and Regional Cooperation Manon Bheenick has said.
</P>
<P>
Bheenick said this in an interview during the Windhoek summit
of Southern African Development Community (SADC) on economic
issues, the Mozambican News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We have reached an agreement with the Mozambican government
on the establishment of a Mozambican-Mauritian mixed committee
for the development of the special economic zone," Bheenick was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two governments reached the agreement in
February when a Mauritian business delegation paid a visit to
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
However, Bheenick said that it is still too early to tell the
total amount of investment needed in the establishment of the
special economic zone.
</P>
<P>
But the Mauritian minister pledged that the project will cover
about 100,000 hectares, saying that "we will construct roads,
houses and other social infrastructures in this area."
</P>
<P>
"If things go smoothly, there will be Mauritians coming to
participate in the development in the Valley of Zambeze in
September and October this year," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Bheenick also disclosed that Mauritian government has approved
the program for the restoration and modernization of the Sena
Sugar States, the Mozambican state-owned sugar plant located in
the central Sofala Province. The restoration project will cost
about 80 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two governments also agreed that the business
people, investors and students can pass customs without visa.
</P>
<P>
Bheenick pointed out that through these moves "the trade
between our two countries will increase." 
</P>
</TEXT>
