<HEADLINE> Nigeria, FAO Sign Pact on Swine Fever Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and the Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) Thursday signed a technical cooperation
agreement for the eradication of the African swine fever (ASF) in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the United Nations agency will contribute
364,500 U.S. Dollars to the 541,000-U.S.-Dollar project, the
Nigerian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
FAO has earlier allocated 386,000 U.S. Dollars to finance an
ASF prevention and intervention scheme in nine west African
countries including Nigeria, according to FAO Representative in
Nigeria Hashim A-Shami.
</P>
<P>
The project, he said, is also expected to provide surveillance
training activities for ASF in Nigeria and initiate a systematic
eradication campaign on the disease.
</P>
<P>
ASF, according to Nigerian Agricultural Minister Malami Buwai,
posed astronomical economic loss to farmers.
</P>
<P>
The last epidemic of the disease in the country in 1973 killed
over 30,000 pigs.
</P>
<P>
Last year, an outbreak of the disease, which was then traced
to neighboring Benin, took a heavy toll on the seven-million pig
population in Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
