<HEADLINE> Senate Judiciary Panel Approves Delayed Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Judiciary
Committee Thursday approved the nomination of a friend of
President Bill Clinton as a judge on the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
</P>
<P>
William Fletcher, 52, a law professor at the University of
California-Berkeley, was nominated three years ago, but has been
criticized as too liberal by some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
Fletcher's nomination now goes to the full Senate for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
One of his Republican opponents, Senator John Ashcroft, said
Fletcher's writings "display a disturbing tendency" toward
judicial activism that would lead him to follow his own agenda
rather than legal precedent once on the bench.
</P>
<P>
Democrats have criticized Republicans for slowing their
examinations of Clinton's judicial nominees, creating a backlog of
vacancies and clogging the courts with more work than sitting
judges can handle.
</P>
<P>
Clinton had agreed to also nominate Barbara Durham, a
conservative and chief justice of the Washington state Supreme
Court, to the 9th Circuit Court in exchange for a Republican
promise to end resistance to the president's choices for vacancies
on the federal bench, according to Republican Senator Slade Gorton
from Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
