<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Food Program Airlifting Food to Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
said it has started to airlift 2,300 tons of food from Dar es
Salaam to Burundi to feed thousands of displaced and vulnerable
people in need of food aid.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by the organization
Thursday, a Boeing 707 is serving the operation which began early
this week.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft makes two flights to Bujumbura airport with each
carrying 34 tons of food, including powdered milk, corn flour,
soybean flour, oil, rice and beans, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The airlift, which is funded by the European Community
Humanitarian Office (ECHO) at a cost of 1.5 million U.S. Dollars,
will help WFP counteract the shortage of emergency food stocks
resulting from flooding early this year which paralyzed
Tanzania's transport network, it said.
</P>
<P>
The press release said continuing insecurity in Burundi has
caused large number of people to flee their land.
</P>
<P>
While WFP estimated that over 5,000 tons of relief food per
month is currently needed in the central African country to
assist some 345,000 people, the agency has been unable to deliver
more than 44 per cent of the requirement since the beginning of
the year due to transport constraints.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release, at the beginning of last
month, WFP airlifted from Dar es Salaam to Bujumbura 685 tons of
food from Dar es Salaam to Bujumbura for 37,000 malnourished
Burundian children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
