<HEADLINE> U.S., Latin America Cooperate to Protect Dolphin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States and six Latin
American countries Thursday signed a dolphin protection agreement,
allowing the U.S. to lift tuna trade embargoes on participating
countries.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed here by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and representatives of Costa Rica, Ecuador, Mexico,
Nicaragua, Panama and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that it would eliminate dolphin deaths associated
with fishing for tuna. "This is one of the strongest agreements
ever negotiated to conserve marine life."
</P>
<P>
"The agreement will ensure the effective conservation of these
marine resources (dolphins) well into the future. It will also
provide the basis for removing U.S. tuna trade embargoes for
nations which become parties to the agreement," State Department
spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He added it was fully consistent with a 1977 U.S. law which
requires a dolphin protection agreement as a condition for lifting
the trade bans against the affected nations
</P>
<P>
The accord will enter into force after being ratified by four
countries of the seven. 
</P>
</TEXT>
