<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Shrugs at EU Proposal for Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkey showed indifference on
Thursday to a proposal by the European Union (EU) to reestablish
closer bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
A Turkish Foreign Ministry statement said the EU has failed to
clarify "all the sensitive issues" included in Turkey's statement
last December.
</P>
<P>
"It would therefore be wiser to hold the meeting of the
(Turkish-EU) Association Council when the circumstances have been
made more appropriate by the EU," it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after an EU meeting held in Brussels on
Wednesday on EU's position on Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The EU members, except Greece, expressed support for the
Strategy Document submitted to the European Council in March,
which agrees to help Turkey get closer to the European body.
</P>
<P>
During his one-day visit to Ankara Tuesday, British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, whose country holds EU's rotating
presidency, said the EU would sidestep Greek hurdles to fulfill
its promise for a 400-million-U.S.-dollar aid to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The EU is apparently trying to placate Ankara in return for its
attendance of the Turkish-EU Association Council meeting
scheduled for May 25 in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, however, said the time is not ripe for such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ankara is dissatisfied with Cook's pledge that other EU members
would work out ways to overcome Greece's veto of the EU financial
aid package to Turkey,
</P>
<P>
"Turkey welcomes the fact that the EU has embarked on a serious
quest to overcome the illegal Greek veto. Yet, it also remains
true that this has not been achieved so far," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that Turkey would most unlikely take part in
the Brussels meeting aimed at bettering the Turkish-EU relations.
</P>
<P>
Turkish-EU ties have been tense since last December when the EU
excluded Turkey from its expansion plan. Turkey has announced to
halt political dialog with the 15-nation group to protest what
Ankara says EU's discriminative attitude towards it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
