<HEADLINE> Republicans Demand Release of Executive Privilege Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Republican-controlled House
of Representatives Thursday called for public release of all
documents related to U.S. President Bill Clinton's assertion of
executive privilege in the Whitewater investigation.
</P>
<P>
Executive privilege is used to protect confidential advice that
a president receives from his advisers.
</P>
<P>
The non-binding resolution passed 259-157 after a highly
partisan debate.
</P>
<P>
Republicans complained that Clinton wrongly invoked the
privilege to protect his personal conduct rather than advice he
received on official matters.
</P>
<P>
Democrats countered that federal judges, not Congress, must
decide whether to release the information because the issue is
before the courts.
</P>
<P>
Democrats called the resolution as retaliation for an
unsuccessful Democratic resolution that sought last week to
criticize Representative Dan Burton, a Republican, for his
handling of a controversial campaign fund-raising investigation.
</P>
<P>
Clinton invoked the executive privilege to prevent two senior
aides from answering grand jury questions about his relationship
with former intern Monica Lewinsky. All documents were placed
under seal by Chief U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson,
who has reportedly rejected Clinton's claim and is considering
whether to release the documents and her ruling.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is expected to appeal, keeping the
issue before the courts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
