<HEADLINE> Canadian Business Confidence Slides: Think Tank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Canadian business confidence
continues to slide, hurt by slumping commodity prices, higher
interest rates and uncertain Asian markets, a leading economic
think-tank said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a seasonal review, the Conference Board of Canada said its
spring index of business attitudes dropped 4.2 percent in the
first quarter to 155.0, the third straight decline for the index.
</P>
<P>
The index has now fallen 10 points from its peak of 165 in the
second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The uncertainty in the world commodity and financial markets
is taking a toll on Canadian business," said Paul Darby, director
of the board's economic services.
</P>
<P>
"Firms are concerned about the sustainability of the current
situation in Canada," he added.
</P>
<P>
The board's survey was conducted in March, when a number of
events forced respondents to lower their expectations. Commodity
prices weakened in the month, resulting in lower profits for most
large Canadian firms.
</P>
<P>
Despite concerns about overall economic conditions, business
remain confident that both labor and inflation costs are under
control, according to the economic think-tank based in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
On the consumer front, the news is better. The board's index of
consumer attitudes moved up 1.8 points to 118.5, due to increased
optimism about job creation.
</P>
<P>
Close to 27 percent of respondents felt there would be more
jobs created over the next six months. This is up from 20 percent
in the fourth quarter of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
