<HEADLINE> LIFFE's Euro Market Strategy For Bond Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The London International Financial
Futures and Options Exchange (LIFFE) Thursday unveiled its
strategy for its existing bond contracts in preparation for the
start of Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
The strategy ensures the smooth transfer and continuous listing
of the LIFFE's Bond contracts through and beyond the launch of the
single currency.
</P>
<P>
Three of the LIFFE's bond contracts will be affected by EMU:
the German Government Bond, the Medium Term Government Bond and
the Italian Government Bond contracts, according to an
announcement by the LIFFE.
</P>
<P>
Because of strong market demand, the board has decided that the
exchange will list euro-denominated futures and options contracts
in parallel with the existing national currency unit (NCU)
contracts.
</P>
<P>
For 1999 delivery months, all of the euro contracts will have a
nominal size of euro 100,000. In addition, the LIFFE intends that
most other elements of the contract specifications of the euro
contracts will be identical to those of the equivalent parallel
listed NCU delivery month.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Hodson, the LIFFE's chief executive, said, "These
initiatives for bond contracts complement the LIFFE's Euro Market
strategy for short-term interest rate (STIR) and for equity index
products." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
