<HEADLINE> Nippon Credit Bank's Rating to BBB- From BBB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Fitch IBCA, the international rating
agency, has downgraded the Long-term rating of Japan's Nippon
Credit Bank to "BBB-" from BBB, and the bank's Short-term rating
is affirmed at "F2."
</P>
<P>
The agency's Long-term rating of Nippon Credit Bank (NCB) has
remained unchanged since 1995, according to an announcement by
Fitch IBCA Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It had long recognized that the bank was likely to suffer such
large loan losses and had premised its securities ratings on
support from the Japanese authorities.
</P>
<P>
This support was duly provided in the spring of 1997 when the
Ministry of Finance coordinated a rescue for the bank, including a
capital injection by the Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Having supported the bank only last year, Fitch IBCA does not
expect the authorities to withdraw their support in the
short-term; it is therefore making no change to its Short-term
rating of "F2."
</P>
<P>
In the long term, however, the agency had some concerns over
the extent of support that may be given to various classes of
creditor.
</P>
<P>
It is therefore lowering its Long-term rating of NCB to "BBB-,"
Fitch IBCA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
