<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Irish to Approve Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Thursday urged voters in Ireland and Northern Ireland to vote
"yes" on an historic peace deal and "embrace a common future in
peace."
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the call in a White House ceremony to sign the
U.S. ratification of the expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) to include Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
"I'd like to put in one last plug for the vote in Ireland and
Northern Ireland tomorrow," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"And I hope that those fine people will lift the burden of the
last 30 years from their shoulder and embrace a common future in
peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Irish voters will decide the fate on Friday of a
U.S.-brokered accord that aims to put an end to the armed conflict
on the status of the Northern Island.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord was signed by all the parties concerned in
Belfast on April 10. 
</P>
