<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 50,000 Villagers Return Home in Northwest Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 21 (Xinhua) -- About 50,000 people who had fled
to bushes and volcano forests, or to the Democratic Republic of
Congo in the past months are massively returning to their homes
in the prefectures of Gisenyi and Ruhengeri, Rwanda News Agency
(RNA) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The movement started about a month ago," the assistant
prefect in charge of administrative affairs in Gisenyi, northwest
Rwanda, Gerard Ngoga indicated. "With this week alone, we have
in some communes registered up to 2,000 displaced people flocking
out of hideouts everyday."
</P>
<P>
According to Ngoga, in a period of less than one month, 14,000
resettled in their villages in Mutura commune northeast of
Gisenyi town, another 10,000 were registered in neighboring
Rwerere, both on the fringe of the volcano mountains marking the
porous border with the DRC.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Gisenyi government officials dispatched 10 tons
of food items, and drugs to Rwerere where the returning
internally-displaced villagers are said to be faced with hunger,
and malnutrition-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
In neighboring Ruhengeri prefecture, about 26,000 villagers
from the communes of Nkuli, Kinigi, and Mukingo also left
hideouts in the forests of the volcano mountains.
</P>
<P>
Reasons pushing these people to return to their homes they had
abandoned months ago range from hunger and starvation in
hideouts, exposure and atrocities committed by the militia, RNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
"Security has returned in most of these communes," the prefect
of Ruhengeri, Boniface Rucagu was quoted as saying. "These
people had been forced to follow 'infiltrators' in the mountains,
but today they are massively dissociating themselves with the
enemy."
</P>
<P>
The word "infiltrator" is used by the Rwandan government to
indicate the Hutu extremist militia, made of the notorious
"Interahamwe" -- those who attack together -- and some former
government soldiers behind the waves of violence prevailing in
northwest and some parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the villagers who are now breaking free from the
militia, local residents were told to follow them to the
territory under their control. The villagers were asked to flee
the "Tutsi" government army for a sanctuary in caves and forests.
</P>
<P>
Some returning villagers interviewed by RNA affirmed Thursday
that all was but lies, the militia are said to have used them as
mere human shields.
</P>
<P>
Although no one has visited these hideouts to know exactly
what the situation there looks like, the villagers accuse the
militia of extreme barbarity.
</P>
<P>
In one of the many recent cases of such atrocities, the
militia reportedly slaughtered 30 babies crying for food at
Bisate, a sector in Kinigi commune, in Ruhengeri on the foot of
Sabyinyo volcano.
</P>
<P>
"There are other numerous cases of such suppression of human
life," the returnees said.
</P>
<P>
"Even the old ones who fail to accomplish a special mission
are killed in cold blood,'' they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
