<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Officials Call for Additional Support for IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Fed chief Alan Greenspan and two
senior officials of the Clinton administration Thursday called on
U.S. congressmen to give the green light to additional 18 billion
U.S. dollar assistance for the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The effects of the Asian crisis are just now being felt in the
United States and there is still a slim possibility that the
financial turmoil in the region could widen into a much greater
threat to the global economy, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan noted.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the U.S. House Agriculture Committee,
Greenspan and two government officials, Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin and Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, stressed that the
U.S. economy had not yet absorbed the full impact of the financial
turmoil that struck Indonesia, Thailand and South Korea last year.
</P>
<P>
"We have so far avoided the type of continuing downward spiral
that some feared," Greenspan said in his testimony before the
committee.
</P>
<P>
But he also reminded the congressmen that there remained a
"small but not negligible probability that the upset in East Asia
could have unexpectedly large negative effects on Japan, Latin
America, and eastern and central Europe that, in turn, could have
repercussions elsewhere, including the United States."
</P>
<P>
Greenspan also stressed that there was a lag between the
financial meltdown in currency and stock markets and the impact of
those adverse developments on the overall world economy.
</P>
<P>
"The effects of the Asian crisis on the real economies of the
immediately affected countries, as well as on our own economy, are
only now just being felt," he added.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the committee, Rubin said that the United
States has "critical economic and national security interests in
restoring financial stability in Asia". Nearly 40 percent of the
U.S. agricultural production is exported -- and 40 percent of
those exports go to Asia. In general, 30 percent of U.S. exports
go to Asia, supporting millions of U.S. jobs, and this country now
exports more to Asia than Europe, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also stressed that the United States also has critical
national security interest in seeing a restoration of financial
stability in the region. "We have 100,000 troops based in Asia,
37,000 on the Korean Peninsula alone. A stable and prosperous Asia
is more likely to be a peaceful Asia," he underlined.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary for the United States to do everything sensible
to help these Asian countries get back on track, he said.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan appeared Thursday with Rubin and Glickman as part of
a continuing effort by the administration and the Fed to win
approval for 18 billion dollars in additional support for the IMF,
whose resources have been depleted by the need to organize more
than 100 billion dollars in financial bailouts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
