<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Urged to Curb Harmful Traditional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Committee of Harmful
Traditional Practices in Ethiopia urged Thursday that policies
and awareness campaigns be launched to curb harmful traditional
practices in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, the call came after a
study made by the committee on 65 nationalities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The study revealed the existence in Ethiopia of 140 harmful
traditional practices and 20 of them are extremely harmful.
</P>
<P>
Female genital mutilation in particular is rampant in the
Amhara, Oromiya, Tigray, Afar and Somali regions, said the study.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Harmful Traditional Practices was set up in
1986 under the ministry of health. It assumed full autonomy in
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
