<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Ports Handles Record International Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Canadian ports, led by Vancouver,
handled a record amount of international cargo in 1997, Statistics
Canada said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The growth of international cargo pushed the total tonnage
handled by the ports to its highest level in nine years, the
statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Total international cargo reached 282.3 million tons, an 8.5
percent increase from 1996 and an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
Shipment of four bulk commodities -- crude oil, coal, iron ore
and wheat -- were responsible for the increase in international
marine cargo.
</P>
<P>
Vancouver is by far the busiest port in Canada. In 1997, it
handled a record 71.8 million tons of cargo, almost one-fifth of
the total cargo handled at Canadian ports.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Vancouver was the number one port in Canada for coal,
wheat and sulphur and the number two port for container traffic.
</P>
<P>
International shipments accounted for 99 percent of the port's
total traffic in 1997, and 92 percent of these shipments were
outbound to foreign ports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
