<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls Suharto's Resignation "Wise Decision" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Thursday called Indonesian President Suharto's resignation a "wise
decision" and pledged to support what he said was "democratic
reform."
</P>
<P>
"I welcome the wise decision made less than 24 hours ago by
President Suharto in Indonesia," Clinton said in the Rose Garden
at the opening of a ceremony about the expansion of NATO.
</P>
<P>
"The United States stands ready to work, as we have with other
nations in the past, to support Indonesia's leaders and people as
they pursue democratic reform," he added.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time that Clinton made comments on Suharto's
resignation. On Wednesday night, Clinton expressed his welcome to
the move by Suharto shortly after the Indonesian president
announced his resignation in Jakarta on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in a statement that Suharto's decision "provides
an opportunity to begin a process leading to a real democratic
transition for Indonesia."
</P>
<P>
The White House took a cautious approach, however, on what the
United States would do after Suharto's resignation.
</P>
<P>
"We're assessing what has happened," White House spokesman Mike
McCurry told reporters. "You all don't know and we don't know at
this point how events are going to unfold there in coming days."
</P>
<P>
He said the United States would be prudent "to look before we
leap."
</P>
<P>
McCurry said the United States would consult with other
countries about whether the International Monetary Fund should
renew aid to Indonesia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
