<HEADLINE> S. Africa Welcomes Suharto's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa welcomed
Indonesian President Suharto's resignation, the Foreign Affairs
Department said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The South African government has welcomed President Suharto's
decision to withdraw from his position as president of Indonesia
with immediate effect, as a bold and courageous step," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"It believes that this decision was taken in the interests of
the people of Indonesia."
</P>
<P>
The statement said the South African government urges
Suharto's successor, Baharuddin Jusuf Habibie, as well as all the
other Indonesian leaders, to use this opportunity to ensure a
speedy return to political stability and economic recovery in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, South African President Nelson Mandela said
Suharto's resignation was a matter for the Indonesian people.
</P>
<P>
Suharto, who had been president for 32 years, announced
resignation Thursday among pressure from parliament and
opposition parties after his country was torn apart by riots.
</P>
<P>
Habibie has been sworn in as new president of the populous
southeast Asian country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
