<HEADLINE> Clinton,Yeltsin Discuss Tensions in South Asia on Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
spoke on Thursday with Russian President Boris Yeltsin by
telephone about the tensions in South Asia caused by India's
nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed how to persuade India's neighbor,
Pakistan, to refrain from setting off a nuclear explosion, said
White House spokesman Michael McCurry.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that the two leaders also talked about how
they might encourage India "to think very seriously about its
international obligations" and the advisability of signing the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
In their 15-minute conversation, the two also discussed
regional issues, but they did not discuss the timing of a Clinton
trip to Moscow, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders met in Birmingham, Britain four days ago after
they attended a summit of the Group of Seven industrialized
countries plus Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
