<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Film Condemned in Nanjing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Some historians and survivors of
the Nanjing Massacre held a seminar at the Jiangdongmen Memorial
Hall here today to refute a distorting Japanese film, which began
premier in Japan early in May.
</P>
<P>
Worked out by right-wing forces in Japan with an investment of
1.5 billion yen, "Pride, an Instant in a Lifetime" has whitewashed
Japanese aggressor troops, denied the Nanjing Massacre and sung
the praises of Hideki Tojo, the top Japanese war criminal during
the World War II.
</P>
<P>
The film makes people indignant for it denies the large-scale
massacre in Nanjing in 1937 and says that the testimonies of
witnesses are nearly valueless, according to Zhu Chengshan,
director of the memorial hall.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that the witnesses who appeared at the International
Military Tribunal for the Far East as shown in the film did exist,
and some of them are still alive. However, the film has distorted
the testimonies of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the large amount of remaining bones of slain
Chinese soldiers and innocent civilians and the photos and video
tapes shot by a foreign clergyman provide irrefutable evidences to
breaking the lies of the film's scriptwriter and director, Zhu
said.
</P>
<P>
"I am a witness of history," said 80-year-old Li Xiuying,
pointing the scars on her face. On December 19, 1937, then
pregnant Li was stabbed more than 30 times by Japanese soldiers
for refusing to be raped.
</P>
<P>
She managed to survive following treatment by an American
doctor. But her child was lost.
</P>
<P>
Historians Gao Xingzu and Sun Zhaiwei with the Nanjing
University and the Jiangsu Academy of Social Sciences said at the
seminar that the film, which confuses right and wrong and tampers
with history, will surely be spurned by the people all around the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Flays India's Statements on Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government's recent
statements about its nuclear tests are "designed to weave further
webs of deception to conceal India's hegemonic and aggressive
designs," a Pakistani Foreign Office spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was responding to reports that India had
announced a moratorium on nuclear testing and was prepared to
discuss with Pakistan its "no first use" of nuclear weapons
proposal.
</P>
<P>
"Evidently, the Indian government's statement is meant to
placate international opinion on the nuclear test issue and
designed to weave further webs of deception to conceal India's
hegemonic and aggressive designs," he said in a press statement.
</P>
<P>
"The world has now seen India's true face. A country with
India's record of war, conflicts and subversion against each one
of its neighbors, (and) now armed with nuclear weapons is a threat
to global peace and security," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The sort of jingoism and chauvinism being displayed by India
bodes ill for the region and its own poor and suffering people,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on India's "no first use" proposal, the spokesman
noted that the Indian leadership has already categorically stated
they would not hesitate to use nuclear weapons, whereas all states
are obliged under the U.N. Charter to refrain from any threat or
use of force, conventional or nuclear.
</P>
<P>
Indian Home Minister Lal Krishna Advani's statements "are
indicative of the total recklessness and fundamentalists euphoria
generated in India by its nuclear tests," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Advani said on Tuesday that Dew Delhi would take a tough stance
over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
This "reflects India's desire to secure its occupation of
Kashmir through nuclear blackmail," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
