<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Malaysia Qualify for Thomas Cup Badminton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Defending champions Indonesia
were on their way to a record eleventh victory when they won over
arch rivals China 3-2 in the semi-finals at the 20th Thomas Cup
Badminton Finals here Friday, which set a championship final
against five-time winners Malaysia Sunday.
</P>
<P>
With the semi-final defeat, four-time winners China would
finish at the current world team championships tied third placers
for a fourth time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia scored a hard-won 3-2 semi-final victory over
runners-up Denmark Friday afternoon, with the outcome remaining
uncertain until after the final singles match.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia held Denmark to a 2-2 tie on team scores in the
semi-finals in the afternoon and Denmark's world eleven Kenneth
Jonassen lost the decisive rubber 1-2 to Malaysia's 29th-ranked
Roslin Hashim.
</P>
<P>
Jonassen became the man of the day Wednesday when he brought
Denmark to a 3-2 victory over China, with his come-from-behind win
over world number five Dong Jiong in Group A final match.
</P>
<P>
The same scene repeated at Hong Kong's Elizabeth Stadium court
again Friday afternoon when the 23-year-old European championships
runner-up from Denmark was left facing a match he had to win to
keep his team's hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
Losing the opening game 15-18, Malaysia's Hashim won the second
with his persistent play and he kept pressing on his Danish
opponent in the third. An increasingly impatient Jonassen lost the
ground step by step and conceded the game 8-15 and the match. A
disappointed Jonassen smashed his racket onto the floor at the end
of the match, which lasted five hours.
</P>
<P>
After obtaining a fifth triumph in 1992, the Malaysians
finished runners-up in 1994 but failed to reach the last four in
the 1996 tournament in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Seeking their first victory after coming out tied third in the
past three tournaments in a row, China faced a win-or-die prospect
when taking on the Indonesians in the other semi-final Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
China's world number two Sun Jun floored Indonesian ace and
world number seven Heryanto Arbi 2-1 in the opening singles. But
the team score was soon leveled by the Indonesians when their
world number two duet Ricky Subagja and Rexy Sigit beat the
11th-ranked Chinese Liu Yong and Zhang Wei two games to none.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's 12th-ranked Hendrawan downed world number three Luo
Yigang of China 2-1 in the second singles, for his second win over
Luo in six months' time.
</P>
<P>
The merciless Indonesians continued to take the following
doubles 2-0 to stand an unscalable 3-1 lead on team score, which
ensured a victory for the Indonesians in spite of a singles match
left.
</P>
<P>
However, Indonesia's 24th-ranked Indra Wijaya lost to China's
world number five Dong Jiong 0-2.
</P>
<P>
Defending champions Indonesia will play runners-up China in the
Uber Cup final Saturday evening while the Thomas Cup final is set
for Sunday evening with defending champions Indonesia taking on
Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
