<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Mayor Decides Not to Seek Another Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Marion Barry, mayor of the
nation's capital, has announced that he will not seek a fifth
term.
</P>
<P>
Barry's announced Thursday that he would not seek re-election
when his current term expires next January 2.
</P>
<P>
Barry, 62, has been the city's mayor for 14 of the last 18
years. In 1990 he left office in disgrace after being videotaped
smoking crack cocaine in a downtown hotel. After serving a
six-month prison sentence, he staged a political comeback, first
winning a city council seat and then reclaiming the mayor's office
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Congress took control of most of city government from
the mayor and council as a condition for federal assistance to
solve massive financial problems facing the city. Since then, the
municipal government has been under the control of a
presidentially appointed five-member financial control board.
</P>
<P>
Barry did not say what he would do after leaving government.
But business leaders and longtime supporters have been reportedly
trying to line up financial commitments to help him make a smooth
transition from politics to private life.
</P>
<P>
Already four members of the city council are seeking to succeed
Barry.
</P>
<P>
A Republican member of the council, Carol Schwartz, who lost
the 1994 mayoral election to Barry, has said that she will again
seek her party's nomination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
