<HEADLINE> Pakistan Opposition Supports Govt Over India Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's former prime minister
and leader of the opposition, Benazir Bhutto, Friday offered
unconditional support to the government against Indian threats to
Pakistan's national security.
</P>
<P>
Benazir announced her support for the government over the
Indian threats at a meeting with Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan
in Pakistan's largest city of Karachi, according to the Associated
Press of Pakistan (APP).
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the foreign minister briefed
Benazir about the situation arising from the nuclear tests
conducted by India earlier this month, APP said.
</P>
<P>
Benazir assured Gohar Ayub Khan of her support in the face of
any threat to the security and territorial integrity of Pakistan,
APP said.
</P>
<P>
"If Pakistan is attacked or its security comes under threat of
Indian aggression, we will forget our differences and support the
national interests," Benazir was quoted as saying. "We will try to
unite the whole country." 
</P>
</TEXT>
