<HEADLINE> Mongolia, Japan See "Comprehensive Partnership" Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia and Japan agreed to
establish a 21st-century-oriented "comprehensive partnership"
during Mongolian President Nachagyn Bagabandy's recent trip to
Japan.
</P>
<P>
The partnership is considered one of Bagabandy's major
achievements during the May 11-15 visit to Japan, Director of the
Presidential Office Bayar told a press conference on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The "comprehensive partnership" covers such areas as bilateral
ties, a mutually beneficial trading partnership, cooperation in
science and technology, education, culture and humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the largest donor to Mongolia, with loans mainly
provided for Mongolia's infrastructure and mining sectors.
</P>
<P>
From 1977 to the end of last year, Japan donated 38.7 billion
yen (293 million U.S. dollars) to Mongolia and gave it technical
assistance worth 11.6 billion yen (88 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Key exports to Japan include copper concentrate and
cashmere. And imports from Japan account for 8 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Bagabandy visited Japan while he was a parliament
speaker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
