<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Rebuts Blame for Stalling Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said Friday that Israel has been unjustly accused of
stalling the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to foreign diplomats in Jerusalem, Netanyahu noted
that the peace process had collapsed two years ago in a wave of
terrorist attacks and the failure of the Palestinian self-rule
government to fulfill its commitments to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"We had a collapse of peace, maybe not in the way this was
perceived in every capital around the world, but the way it was in
practice here," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that "we had the collapse of the basic deal of
Oslo," adding that the principle of Oslo Accords was put
forwarded by the former Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who said
"we give the Palestinians the territory, they fight the
terrorists from their territory."
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu said, "We give them territory, they did not
fight terrorists."
</P>
<P>
And as a result, he said, there has been an explosion of
terrorism, which was unprecedented in Israel. And in a period of
two and an half years, 250 Israelis were killed in terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Palestinian National Authority (PNA) fought
terrorism only in a "partial" and "incomplete" way.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu took power in June, 1996. And since his right-wing
government started the building of a Jewish settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem last March, Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have
been deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians have accused Netanyahu of intentionally stalling
the peace process. But Netanyahu insisted that the agreement with
the Palestinians should not endanger the security interests of
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
