<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Nations Call for Balanced Interests Within WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Heavy debates became a prominent
feature of the second ministerial conference of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) in Geneva on May 18-20, as the developing world
called for balanced interests within the organization, while the
developed nations tried to gain more through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
High on the list of their debates were issues such as the
implementation of the existing trade agreements, the built-in
agenda and future activities, as well as the date and venue of the
next ministerial conference.
</P>
<P>
Members from the developing world have argued that the WTO
should put more emphasis on the needs of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 and early 1998, after reviewing trade policies of some
European Union nations and Japan, the WTO secretariat said their
tariffs were not at a satisfactorily low level and there were even
"tariff peaks" in sectors like agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, on the very first day of the conference, WTO
Director-General Renato Ruggiero called on all members to fully
meet their commitments.
</P>
<P>
"Full implementation is essential to the credibility of our
system and its potential to carry the weight of future
responsibilities," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"And we need to recognize that a great part of the answer to
this problem has to be found in improving the functioning of the
existing bodies of the WTO, notably the General Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the built-in agenda and future activities, there have
been apparent differences among the members.
</P>
<P>
In their speeches at the conference, Secretary-General of the
United Nations Conference on Trade and Development Rubens
Ricupero, South African President Nelson Mandela, Cuban President
Fidel Castro and trade officials from Asia, Africa and Latin
America all urged the WTO to take into account the concerns of the
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that the priority should be to enrich the poor
rather than to make the rich richer when new negotiations would be
launched.
</P>
<P>
"The building of developing countries' capacity to defend their
interests effectively in trade negotiations, and to establish the
universality of the WTO, is an essential task," said Ricupero.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan,
Ricupero said that "priority should be given to trade barriers
targeting the exports of developing countries in both goods and
services" although the trade liberalization process must maintain
its momentum.
</P>
<P>
For their part, officials from the advanced industrialized
countries wanted to see the negotiations expanded to other
areas. Some members led by the United States wish to have an
agreement on electronic commerce as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"We can no longer afford to take seven years to finish a trade
round as happened during the Uruguay Round," U.S. President Bill
Clinton told the conference during his one-hour stopover in Geneva
on May 18.
</P>
<P>
"We should explore whether there is a way to tear down barriers
without waiting for every issue in every sector to be resolved,"
he said. "I am confident we can go about the task of negotiating
trade agreements in a way that is faster and better than today."
</P>
<P>
Last but not least, the WTO members discussed the date of the
next ministerial conference.
</P>
<P>
As the ministerial conference is biennial, the third was
originally scheduled to be held in 2000.
</P>
<P>
However, under the WTO agenda, members are to negotiate
agriculture and services by the end of 1999 and early 2000
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Many members from the developing countries believe they are
encountering difficulties at home in implementing the existing
agreements so that it is unnecessary to have new negotiations
other than those already on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
To fulfill those tasks will take a lot of time and resources,
said the members from the developing world. So they do not want to
have the third conference to be held one year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, to start new negotiations early would make it more
difficult for those applying to join the WTO. If they cannot have
their WTO memberships in time, they will have no say in the
negotiations and have to meet new terms set by their opponents.
</P>
<P>
As a compromise, the U.S. agreed in its proposal that the
economic, financial and development needs of the developing
countries should be taken into account in future activities.
</P>
<P>
At its closing session, the WTO decided to hold its third
ministerial conference in the United States in the fourth quarter
of 1999. But the exact date and venue of the next conference will
await the decision by the WTO General Council.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the organization adopted a U.S. proposal on global
electronic commerce, suggesting that no customs duties be imposed
on electronic transmissions.
</P>
<P>
As head of the Chinese delegation at the conference, Long
Yongtu pointed out that when the multilateral trading system turns
50, the WTO must face two realities: the political reality that of
its 132 members, more than 100 are from the developing world, and
the economic reality that world trade is more and more integrated.
</P>
<P>
In such circumstances, he said, the WTO is facing a severe
challenge: how to ensure that all its members, big or small, rich
or poor, share the benefits of the economic globalization on a
justified basis in the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminar on Asian Financial Crisis Closes in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The stable development of China's
