<HEADLINE> Compulsory Education Project Launched in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The State Compulsory Education
Project for Poverty-stricken Regions was launched today in the
Tibet Autonomous Region, according to the local government.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese central government will allocate special funds of
137 million yuan (about 17 million US dollars) over the next three
years for carrying out the project, the biggest nationwide
educational program in Chinese history, in the autonomous region's
69 counties and regions.
</P>
<P>
The local government will support the undertaking to the tune
of 89.3 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be mainly spent on building new primary schools
In addition, a total of 153 primary schools and four high schools
will be renovated or enlarged over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
After the completion of the project the number of Tibetan
primary school students will rise to 310,000 from the current
260,000, and the rate of school-age Tibetan children attending
school is expected to rise to 87 percent in the year 2000 from 73
percent in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
