<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's ANC to Lead 1999 Election, Says Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's African National
Congress (ANC) would remain the dominant party in the 1999 general
elections and the National Party (NP)'s position as the number one
opposition party could be seriously challenged, a local poll said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
While the ANC's support had dropped from 58 percent in November
last year to 54 percent in May, it was likely to maintain the leading
position for some time, said the Markinor's poll.
</P>
<P>
The NP's support fell from 12 percent to 10 percent over the same
period, which benefited the United Democratic Movement (UDM) and the
Democratic Party (DP), South African Press Association quoted the poll
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The UDM's support had increased from four to five percent, and the
DP's backing gained from three percent to five percent.
</P>
<P>
Support for the Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP), the largest
black-based opposition party, remained at five percent.
</P>
<P>
The poll said the DP's further growth potential was questionable as
the party's profile was predominantly white, middle class South
Africans.
</P>
<P>
The UDM, which has a black and a white as co-leaders, seemed to be
potentially the only real competition for the ANC, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
Other analysts echoed the sentiments of the poll, saying the NP was
under siege as the gap between it and the DP and the UDM was
closing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
