<HEADLINE> French Hospital Uses Robot to Conduct Heart Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A hospital in Paris has conducted
open heart surgeries on six patients suffering from cardiac
diseases with a robot in the past two weeks, reported the daily Le
Figaro on Friday.
</P>
<P>
A team of doctors led by Professor Carpentier and Professor
Deloche at the Broussals Hospital here conducted their first open
heart surgery on May 7 with a robot.
</P>
<P>
Equiped with surgical instruments in its arms which were guided
by messages from the doctors, the robot completed four operations
of alteration of cardiac valves, one related on hearing, and one
heart bypass.
</P>
<P>
Doctors of Broussals Hospital began to use computers to conduct
surgery two years ago, because it could help increase skills and
precision and reduce the surface of thorax incisions on patients.
</P>
<P>
Operating with robot can solve all the problems of precision
and traumatizing in classical operations, reduce the surface of
incisions, and overcome the difficulties in operating on smaller
incisions, said the doctors.
</P>
<P>
"It is a hand within the human body, but which has a greater
skill than human hand," said Professor Carpentier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
