<HEADLINE> Lesotho on Alert After Arms Theft in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's security forces are
on the alert for any possible insurrection on the eve of the
country's general elections after a massive arms theft from a
South African military base last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The move followed indications that South African police are
looking at Lesotho as the final destination for the large
consignment, Sowetan paper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We are not ruling out the possibility that the arms might be
headed this way for the purpose of destabilizing the general
election planned for Saturday," a Lesotho security forces
official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We are on the alert and ready for any eventuality," Major
Bolutu Makoaba said.
</P>
<P>
A confirmed 117 items were stolen from the Tempe base near the
central South African city of Bloemfontein, the biggest arms
theft in the past five years. They included rocket launchers,
mortars, automatic rifles and two army vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Six black men, including a member of the South African
National Defense Force (SANDF) at the Tempe base, have been
arrested. The two vehicles have been recovered, but the arms
were still missing.
</P>
<P>
One of the two missing vehicles, a Mamba armored vehicle used
to transport the arms, was found between Bloemfontein and the
Lesotho border, the paper quoted army sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, South African police Thursday dismissed as
speculation stories that the arms could be headed for Lesotho or
be used for shady forces inside South Africa. They said
investigations were continuing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
