<HEADLINE> Iran Expresses Concern over Indian Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Seyed Mohammad
Khatami has expressed concern over India's nuclear tests and
voiced support for Pakistan's efforts to deal with the emerging
security scenario.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn all moves against nuclear non-proliferation and
development of weapons of mass destruction," Khatami said in a
telephone conversation with Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, according
to a report by the Associated Press of Pakistan Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sharif briefed Khatami about Islamabad's concern over the
Indian nuclear tests and said: "They pose a grave threat to
Pakistan's security."
</P>
<P>
"We never wanted to explode nuclear devices and exacerbate
tension in the region by entering into an arms race," Sharif was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In response, Khatami pledged his support for Pakistan's efforts
and said Tehran is ready to work with Islamabad to maintain
regional peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said the Iranian government had already conveyed its
concern to New Delhi over its nuclear tests. "We are greatly
disturbed over the aggravation of the regional security
situation."
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharazi also talked with his
Pakistani counterpart Gohar Ayub Khan by telephone and reiterated
Iran's concern over the nuclear tests. "Such steps will accelerate
arms race and increase tension in the region," Kharazi said.
</P>
<P>
Underlining Teheran's efforts to keep the Indian Ocean and the
Pacific region free of nuclear weapons, Kharazi said: "In our
opinion nuclear proliferation is against peace and security of the
world."
</P>
<P>
Iran Wednesday summoned New Delhi's ambassador to Tehran to
officially convey its concern over the Indian nuclear tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
