<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Following are major news items
in leading U.S. newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- B.J. Habibie outlined a program of reforms, clean government
and economic responsibility that addressed criticisms leveled
against his predecessor, President Suharto, who resigned under
pressure. Habibie pledged to dedicate himself to democratization,
but many of the protesters remain unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
-- In a policy shift, the Clinton Administration has pledged to
sign the international treaty that bans anti-personnel land
mines. But the administration's pledge, made in a letter from the
national security adviser, Samuel Berger, has a caveat: the United
States will agree to sign the treaty only if alternatives to the
most powerful land mines can be found.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Marion Barry announced Thursday that he would not seek a
fifth term as mayor of Washington, D.C., relinguishing his hold on
an office he defined and used to dominate politics in the district
for most of the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Senate on Thursday overwhelmingly decided to strip all
special legal protections for cigarette makers from the national
tobacco bill, handing public health advocates both a key victory
and a new worry over the bill's future.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. House Speaker Gingrich said Congress would seek to cut
more taxes than the GOP's chief target, the so-called marriage
penalty that taxes spouses filing jointly at a higher rate than if
they filed as singles. The House five-year budget proposal calls
for about 100 billion dollars in cuts: the Senate's measure lists
about 30 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- Pager service was restored to tens of millions of customers
after the failure of a PanAmSat satellite Tuesday disrupted
communications in the United States. The firm's contracts hold it
responsible for compensating customers only for the time service
was lost, not the consequences of missed appointments and spoiled
deals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
