<HEADLINE> Philippines' Rice Imports Hit Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines has bought a record
1.35 million tons of rice to make up for the shortfall in domestic
harvests due to the El Nino weather phenomenon, local television
Citynet reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The television quoted officials of the Department of
Agriculture as saying the Philippines has contracted a record 1.35
million tons of rice from neighboring countries for delivery this
year.
</P>
<P>
Citing an earlier government report, Citynet said the country's
unmilled rice harvest in the first quarter of the year dropped to
2.22 million tons from the year-ago volume of 2.56 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Department said earlier it did not expect the
rice harvest to improve in the second quarter because of
below-normal rainfall in the country's rice-growing areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Philippine meteorologists said there was a
possibility of a La Nina weather pattern which would bring
torrential rains to the country in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
The fourth quarter rice harvest accounts for 40 to 45 percent
of the country's total rice production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
