<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Decriminalizes Homosexuality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus decriminalized homosexuality
Thursday, a move demonstrating that Cyprus lawmakers have at last
given way to pressure from the Council of Europe (CoE).
</P>
<P>
A government-proposed bill decriminalizing homosexuality was
passed by the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
The CoE had given Cyprus until May 29 to comply with a decision
of the European Court of Human Rights, or face serious
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
The court, in response to a Cypriot gay's appeal, ruled in 1993
that criminalizing homosexuality was a violation of human rights
and one's private life.
</P>
<P>
Homosexuality was banned in Cyprus until Alecos Modinos, a
Cypriot gay activist took his case and won a ruling from the Court.
</P>
<P>
The ruling, however, has met strong opposition from the Cyprus
Church, which believes that homosexuality is against the Greek
Orthodox religion.
</P>
<P>
In order to reassure the Church, amendments were made to the
bill making certain aspects of homosexuality a crime.
</P>
<P>
A homosexual act between two men in public or involving a
person under 18 is an offense with a maximum penalty of five years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
Anyone found guilty of a homosexual act accompanied by violence
may be given a maximum 14-year prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
Indecent behavior intended to provoke a homosexual act between
two men is also a crime with a maximum penalty of one year in
prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
