<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Develops High Yielding Varieties of Crops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Institute of Nuclear
Agriculture (BINA) has developed eight new high yielding varieties
(HYV) of crops, The Daily Star daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
These eight HYVs of crops, developed by BINA by using mutation
breeding techniques, include paddy, jute, mustard seed and tomato,
which not only can give higher yield but also make the life circle
of crops shorter, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
BINA has also developed a new kind of low-cost,
easily-applicable bio-fertilizer named Rhizobium, which can keep
the environment favorable and can be used as an alternative to
urea in the cultivation of leguminous crops.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, scientists at BINA have developed 19 HYVs of crops,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
