<HEADLINE> Major Anti-Japanese Victory Commemorated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province held
various activities today to mark the 60th anniversary of the
Chinese army's victory in the Battle of Taierzhuang against the
Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
The battle was fought in mid-1938 at Taierzhuan, a location of
strategic importance. The Chinese forces were commanded by Gen. Li
Zongren of the Kuomintang army, with support from local people and
the forces led by the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
The battle lasted a dozen days, and ended with a victory by the
Chinese army, though it cost thousands of lives on both sides.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting to mark the occasion, provincial government
officials called on all the people to emulate the patriotism
demonstrated by the older generation while making greater
contributions to the country's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people from both at home and abroad who fought in
the battle joined local people in the memorial activities. They
also visited the Taierzhuang Battle Memorial Hall, built in 1993,
which has over 600 exhibits, including documents relics from both
the Chinese and Japanese armies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Adopt Safer Vaccine Against Hepatitis B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese medics will be armed with a
safer vaccine against Hepatitis B next year.
</P>
<P>
The new vaccine, made by a genetic engineering process, will
replace the old type of vaccine, which was produced from blood
supplied by Hepatitis B virus (HBV) carriers.
</P>
<P>
"The old vaccine will be abolished next year, because it has
many shortcomings compared with the new one," said Wei Liang, an
official with the pharmaceuticals administration department of the
Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Blood supplied by HBV carriers carries risks of contamination,
Wei explained.
</P>
<P>
In fact, vaccine made from the blood of carriers was the
world's only choice in the fight against Hepatitis B before the
genetic vaccine appeared in the late 1980s. China introduced the
former one in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The new vaccine, which has been proved to be much safer and
more effective than the old one, has been phased into the domestic
market since it was developed by the Beijing Research Institute of
Biological Products in 1993.
</P>
<P>
China has over 120 million HBV carriers, accounting for about
10 percent of the country's population.
</P>
<P>
"If we take prompt measures to vaccinate as many newborn babies
as possible, the incidence of Hepatitis B will be controlled
within one percent in the coming 50 years," said Prof. Su Chong'ao
of the Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine.
</P>
<P>
He called for a stepped-up vaccination campaign in China's
rural areas, where only 30 to 40 percent of infants are vaccinated
at present, compared with some 90 percent in cities.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health has decided to raise the rural
vaccination rate to 60 percent by the year 2000. Some poor areas
will be given vaccines free, it is learned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
