<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taxation Growth Continues to Slow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The growth rate for China's
industrial and commercial tax revenue continued to slow in April,
according to the State Administration of Taxation (SAT).
</P>
<P>
China collected more than 69.4 billion yuan in industrial and
commercial taxes in the month, up seven percent over the 1997 same
period. The real growth rate stood at 0.2 percent deducting
inertia increases of financial and insurance business tax and
stamps levies on security tradings.
</P>
<P>
The SAT attributed the slowdown to the low economic growth rate
which decreases the sources for taxation levies and the sliding
down of commercial taxes.
</P>
<P>
The tax arrears also occurred during the property transforming
in the process of bankruptcy and merger.
</P>
<P>
SAT figures indicate that domestic value-added and consumption
tax revenue, two major tax items under China's tax system
introduced in 1994, stood at 30.7 billion yuan in April,
down 2.1 percent on a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
Business tax, income taxes collected from foreign-funded
enterprises, personal income taxes, stamp taxes, and taxes levied
on regulating the direction of investment kept rapid development.
</P>
<P>
During the January-April period, the country collected a total
of 241.8 billion yuan of taxes, up 9.1 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
