<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou City Strives to Have 13 Percent GDP Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- This capital city of south
China's Guangdong province is striving to have a 13-percent
increase in the gross domestic product (GDP) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The city's economy has a sound beginning this year,
with the GDP in the first three months increasing by 12 percent
over the same period of 1997, ranking first among the country's
top ten cities.
</P>
<P>
It will take measures to expand overseas markets and perfect
the export products structure, in a bid to increase its export
volume, which accounts for 40 percent of its GDP, according
to an official of the Guangzhou city government.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that the city's export volume rose
by 13 percent in the first quarter of this year, and 70 percent of
its products were sold to Europe, Africa and South America.
</P>
<P>
To heavily invest in infrastructure construction and to
stimulate the citizens' consumption are the city's measures
to ensure the 13 percent increase, said the official.
</P>
<P>
He said Guangzhou will soon launch six national-level large
urban construction projects, meanwhile, the city plans to make
efforts to foster its real estate market and encourage the
residents to buy commodity houses through reducing price and tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
