<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Quality Improves Slightly in Major Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The air quality of some major
Chinese cities improved slightly this week, with Yinchuan
appearing to be the only city with medium pollution, according to
a release by the China Environmental Monitoring Center (CEMC)
today.
</P>
<P>
The air quality report on 33 major cities for May 8-12 shows
that no major city in China suffers from heavy air pollution, but
the atmospheric pollution index (API) of Yinchuan has gone above
200, or the medium level of air pollution, due to dust and sand
produced by construction activities and wind from the nearby
deserts.
</P>
<P>
The number of cities with only slight pollution reached 12 this
week, an increase of 300 percent over the previous week, the
report says.
</P>
<P>
The report gives, as well as the API, the index of sulfur
dioxide (SO2), nitrogen oxide (NOX) and total suspended particles
(TSP).
</P>
<P>
Air quality is listed on five levels by the State Environmental
Protection Administration: An API from 0 to 50 is level I, meaning
excellent air quality; 51 to 100 is level II, or good quality; 101
to 200 is level III, or slight pollution; 201 to 300 is level IV,
or medium pollution; and above 300 is level V, or heavy
pollution.
</P>
<P>
The report says that among the cities with API above 100,
Guangdong, Beijing and Shanghai suffered mostly from NOX, while
Hohhot, Zhengzhou, Chengdu, Jinan, Changchun, Tianjin, Harbin and
Kunming suffered mainly from TSP, and Chongqing from SO2.
</P>
<P>
The air quality for the five coastal cities of Fuzhou, Ningbo,
Beihai, Xiamen and Zhuhai was excellent in the past week,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The 16 cities of Shijiazhuang, Lianyungang, Shenyang, Hangzhou,
Nanjing, Guiyang, Wuhan, Qingdao, Changsha, Dalian, Hefei,
Nanchang, Shenzhen, Nanning, Suzhou and Shantou had good air
quality, according to the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
