<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Rejects U.S. Statement on Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Sudan has rejected the U.S. State
Department statement classifying it as one of the states which are
not cooperative enough in fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Khartoum daily "Al Rai Al Am" Friday quoted the deputy speaker
of the Sudanese National Assembly (parliament) Abdul Aziz Sheddu
as saying that the statement "lacks objectivity and reason."
</P>
<P>
He asserted that the Sudan is committed to combating terrorism
and signed the anti-terrorism agreement at the recent Cairo
conference of Arab interior ministers.
</P>
<P>
Sheddu said his country has amended law to bar Arab citizens
from entering the country without visa in an attempt to guard
against terrorists.
</P>
<P>
He called upon the U.S. to define the cases where the Sudan has
failed to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Department of State issued a statement last Tuesday to
identify the states which Washington considered as being negative
and uncooperative with the U.S. in the combat against
terrorism. Eight countries were enlisted, namely, Afghanistan,
Cuba, Iran, Iraq, Libya, the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea, Sudan and Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
