<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Railway Authorities to Coop in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Railways
Corporation (TRC) and the Tanzania-Zambia Railways Authority
(TAZARA) will join hands in transporting cargo to and from other
African countries.
</P>
<P>
A container terminal is under construction at Kidatu in the
central region of Morogoro, a point close to both TRC's central
railway and the TAZARA line, Business Times Friday quoted Linford
Mboma, the director general of the company, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mboma said the proposed container terminal at Kidatu will be
operational in October if the rehabilitation of a 32 km section
of the railway from Kilosa-Kidete is to be completed. The
section was damaged by floods due to the El Nino weather
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The container terminal will help the transshipment of cargos
to and from South Africa, the Democratic Republic of Congo and
other countries in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
As the two railways have different gauges, a South African
private company is going to monitor the operation of loading and
unloading at the container terminal, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mboma said his company plans to hire 10 locomotives from India
in preparation for handling more cargos.
</P>
<P>
However, the transshipment service is not a joint venture
activity but a service agreed by both sides, Mboma said.
</P>
<P>
The central railway, built when Tanganyika mainland was a
colony in the early years of the century, runs from Dar es Salaam
on the Indian Ocean to Lakes Victoria and Tanganyika. The
Tanzania-Zambia railway was built with the aid of the Chinese
government in the 1970s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
