<HEADLINE> Indian Experts Criticize Govt Moratorium on N-Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Some Indian experts and
intellectuals have criticized the government's announcement of
moratorium on nuclear tests Thursday for its attempt to camouflage
the wider consequences of nuclearization, Press Trust of India
(PTI) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The nuclearists have not been able to define what is a modest,
safe and minimum deterrent so far, noted expert on nuclear weapons
Achin Vanaik said.
</P>
<P>
A hydrogen bomb is not at all needed for a deterrent and "we
even don't need to go for nuclear testing," former army chief
General K. Sundarji said.
</P>
<P>
If the government is ultimately thinking of weaponization and
computer simulations, what kind of the moratorium it is talking
about? asked noted expert on South Asian affairs G. P. Deshpande.
</P>
<P>
Charging the government for encouraging a false debate among
the people, Deshpande said that the government should clarify the
costs involved in the nuclear tests and the development of
delivery systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
