<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar traded
solidly Friday before sliding late in the day in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The currency finished at 63.12 U.S. cents from 62.95 U.S. cents
at Thursday's close, while against the Japanese yen it was 85.76
yen from 85.23 yen.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the day the Australian dollar was also fetching
1.1110 German marks from 1.1125 marks.
</P>
<P>
Peter Whitley, manager of foreign exchange with Colonial State
Bank, said the Australian dollar made a good recovery during the
week, having returned from a low of 61.70 U.S. cents, ahead of
Tuesday morning's intervention by the Reserve Bank of Australia
(RBA), and rose to 63 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar started the week nervously, being
continually sold down over the preceding days as tensions in
Indonesia escalated, and the RBA moved in the early hours of
Tuesday morning to prop it up, driving the currency back one U.S.
cent.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also got a lift Thursday night from a
rebound in the gold price which recaptured the 300 U.S. dollar an
ounce level and was trading at 300.20 U.S. dollars an ounce on the
spot market Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
