<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Finish Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket closed
weaker Friday, with trading interest subdued by regional
instability and the prospect of new companies being floated.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries ended 7.6 points, or 0.28 percent, lower at
2725.9. It traded in a 16 point range.
</P>
<P>
The appointment Thursday of B.J. Habibie as new president of
Indonesia following Soeharto's dramatic resignation had only
served to leave investors waiting for the next development,
according to Macquarie Bank broker Lucinda Chan.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's upheaval, along with the prospect of 10 billion
U.S. dollars in share floats in the coming months, was weighing on
the Australian sharemarket.
</P>
<P>
"It's like watching paint dry," said Chan.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody is prepared to move their funds because people in the
speculative stocks can't get out because they are too weak."
</P>
<P>
The low key trading was reflected in national turnover, which
was valued at 495.5 million U.S. dollars, with the daily average
value of just under 631.2 million U.S. dollars, and volume was
265.6 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Falls of 576 were ahead of rises of 485 with 412 stocks steady.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index lost 15.9 points, or 0.34 percent, to
4726.7.
</P>
<P>
The banking index finished the day down 30.2 points, or 0.51
percent, with National Australia Bank (NAB) the only one of the
four major banks to post gains.
</P>
<P>
NAB finished up three cents at 22.12 Australian dollars,
Westpac bank fell 20 cents to 10.50 Australian dollars, ANZ bank
dropped five cents to 10.92 Australian dollars ahead of its
interim results due next week, and the Commonwealth Bank of
Australia lost 7.3 cents to 18.83 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed down 0.3 points, or 0.03
percent, at 1120.8.
</P>
<P>
Resources stocks were mixed. Diversified miner BHP lost 1.8
cents to 13.64 Australian dollars and Anglo-Australian giant Rio
Tinto fell 10 cents to 20.10 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index lifted 20.5 points, or 1.65 percent, to 1262.3.
Spot gold was trading at 299.90 U.S. dollars an ounce late in
Sydney, steady from Thursday's close. 
</P>
</TEXT>
