<HEADLINE> Airport Police Moving to Chek Lap Kok in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A relocation exercise will start
this month to move the police force stationed at Kai Tak airport
to Chek Lap Kok new airport, which is scheduled to open on July 6.
</P>
<P>
Senior superintendent Wong Ka-sing, commander of the Airport
Police District, told a press conference here Friday: "The move
will be proceeded in phases with the final phase to be completed
upon the commencement of the new airport."
</P>
<P>
Personnel at Kai Tak will be transferred step by step to the
new airport, with 60 officers by the middle of June and 80 by the
day of the new airport in operation.
</P>
<P>
The Chek Lap Kok police station will be in full strength with
417 staff in total on July 6, when the new airport is put to use.
Having started operation in September 1997, the police station now
has 80 officers.
</P>
<P>
Wong said: "Starting from the middle of June, both the Kai Tak
and Chek Lap Kok Airport police stations will be running parallel
for three weeks."
</P>
<P>
"When the new police station becomes fully operational, the Kai
Tak Airport Police Station will cease operation and its area will
be covered by another police division," he added.
</P>
<P>
An ad hoc team was set up in January last year to ensure that
the Chek Lap Kok Police Station is to become operational on
schedule. "We will make the relocation a success," Wong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
