<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multimedia Puts Children at Risk of Inferior Education: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Internet and television may
provide instant access to information but such multimedia put
children at risk of losing their language and social skills, a
conference was told in Australia's port city of Adelaide Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sydney Writers Festival Director John Nieuwenhuizen said the
Internet and other forms of multimedia used in the classroom
relied more on imagery than on language.
</P>
<P>
In Australia, the Internet and other forms of multimedia are
available to residents, including children, at district libraries
and schools free of charge.
</P>
<P>
"In schools there are punishments or rewards for paying
attention, but there are no such punishments or rewards from
television," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Both television and the Internet encourage children to sit
still and passively accept what is put in front of them.
</P>
<P>
"Both give the sensation just by watching a screen that you can
require information without work and without discipline."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Children's Book Council of Australia
conference, Nieuwenhuizen said this visual form of learning puts
children at risk of losing their language and social skills.
</P>
<P>
"I think we are likely, if we follow this path, to end up with
kids whose language skills diminish after years spent on this sort
of visual and image based activities that the multimedia pushes
you towards," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We'll end up with kids who have no idea of how to go about
research without constant rewards, the constant rewards you get
from computers."
</P>
<P>
"They are learning that the world is a passive and
pre-programmed place, and that the click of a mouse is all the
effort required to get information," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nieuwenhuizen said the result was something everyone should be
worried about because reading and remembering things would
eventually become too difficult.
</P>
<P>
"Education is about teaching children how to use their brains
and not about telling them how to use a computer," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
