<HEADLINE> HK, Canada Agrees on Information Technology Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and Canada signed on
Friday a memorandum of understanding (MOU) for the two sides to
foster and promote cooperation on information and communications
technology.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Secretary for Information Technology and Broadcasting
K C Kwong and Canadian Minister of Industry John Manley signed the
MOU, which is the first bilateral arrangement of its kind Hong
Kong has made with other countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the ceremony, Kwong said, the MOU "is a positive
step in the further development of the close and long-standing
relations between Hong Kong and Canada."
</P>
<P>
It focuses on areas such as multimedia and software
applications and products, electronic commerce infrastructure and
policy, broadband networks and applications, and Internet
applications.
</P>
<P>
It will cover a period of five years and can be extended by
mutual agreement.
</P>
<P>
"Canada is advanced in IT development and applications. The
signing of the MOU will enable Hong Kong to benefit from the
experience and expertise of Canada. This will in turn help us
maintain our lead in IT and foster the growth of the local IT
industry," the Hong Kong official noted.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from both sides had met to explore
opportunities for joint ventures and cooperation. They are also
planning to organize joint activities under MOU, according to
Kwong, who was appointed to the current post earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
