<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Stops Selling of Misprinted Stamps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Macao Posts and
Telecommunications Department (CTT) decided on Friday to stop
selling a set of misprinted stamps, causing speculations that the
stamps already sold will add value.
</P>
<P>
CTT announced early Friday morning that the set of stamps in
commemoration of Vasco da Gama's historical voyage to India, which
was issued on Wednesday, was found to have been misprinted.
</P>
<P>
While Gama arrived in India in 1498, the year printed on the
stamps is 1598.
</P>
<P>
It is not known how many stamps have been sold out already.
CTT's planned number of issues was set at 1.90 million pieces.
</P>
<P>
Macao stamps have been left in the cold since the beginning of
this year after a fever in late 1997. CTT has cut the number of
issues from 2.3 million early this year to the current number.
</P>
<P>
But, the misprinted stamps may turn out to be hot pieces, some
market watchers said. Some local stamp dealers reportedly raised
the price immediately on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
