<HEADLINE> Nigeria Pays Heavily to Foreigners for Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has frowned at the inability
of local shippers to handle the country's oil, saying it has to
pay 2.6 million U.S. Dollars each month for foreign companies to
lift the crude to other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
"There is no country where this is done," said Alhaji Buba
Galadima, director-general of the country's National Maritime
Authority, quoted by the Post Express Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There is no American policy which will allow a foreigner to
carry out such goods for them," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nigerian shippers should take up the
challenge of listing crude oil which if they succeed will enable
them to have vessels from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is the leading oil producer in Africa, with an output
of 2.455 million barrels per day, most of which are for export.
</P>
<P>
Galadima noted if Nigeria ship owners wish to compete with
their counterparts in other parts of the world, they have to
comply with international rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
And his agency will leave no stone unturned while enforcing
all these rules and regulations, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
