<HEADLINE> Yeltsin on Settlement of Miner Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
on Friday that the federal authorities had no intention to print
money to pay back wages to the striking miners, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In his regular radio address, Yeltsin resolutely opposed a
proposal to print a few billion rubles, saying "this would push
our economy far back."
</P>
<P>
The proposal was reportedly raised in a bid to put an end to
the explosive situation triggered by miners' strikes in protest at
unpaid wages.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president pointed out that miners' strikes in
various parts of the country have done great damage to the economy
and have threatened to do incalculable damage to the whole country.
</P>
<P>
The blockade of railroads has resulted in millions of rubles of
losses to transportation and factories which can not receive raw
materials, parts and fuels, he said.
</P>
<P>
The strikes began a week ago when miners bloked trains on
trans-Siberian line at Anzhero-Sudzhensk, north of the regional
capital Kemerovo.
</P>
<P>
The federal authorities "are doing their best to alleviate the
passions and pull the coal mining industry out of the crisis,
Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
The president said Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko has sent a
bill to the State Duma under which the costs of the government,
presidential administration and Federal Assembly will be reduced
by a quarter and the saved amounts will be used to help the
miners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
