<HEADLINE> EAGA Participants Urged to Harmonize Trade Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The governments of the Brunei,
Indonesia, Malaysia and the Philippines - East Asean Growth Area
(BIMP-EAGA) have been urged to agree on a harmonized set of trade
practices and procedures.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's Sabah State Chief Minister Yong Teck Lee made the
appeal Friday at the two-day BIMP-EAGA Business Forum '98 - The
International Conference on Business Opportunities and Strategies
being held in Bandar Seri Begawan, Brunei's capital, according to
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
"To overcome the currency problem, the governments are actively
pursuing greater use of domestic currencies in intra-Asian trade.
The Sabah state government is also pursuing the idea of expanding
barter trade within the region as a means to overcome the
problem," he was quoted as saying in his working paper entitled
"Government and Private Sector Partnership in the BIMP-EAGA."
</P>
<P>
He said the success of such a plan will be contingent on
regional governments agreeing to the idea and will open up a new
window of opportunities for the private sector in spite of the
present economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Hence, he said there is an urgency to harmonize a set of trade
practices, procedures and even institutions.
</P>
<P>
Actual projects on the ground, however, were slow in coming and
this low success rate of business formation amongst the BIMP-EAGA
member states could be the result of the economic crisis facing
the region, Yong said.
</P>
<P>
"To further the economic base and scope of BIMP-EAGA, we are
now exploring ways to link the region to other growth areas and
one example at hand is to establish air links with
Indonesia-Malaysia-Thailand Growth Triangle (IMT-GT) via Pulau
Pinang (southern Malaysia) to BIMP-EAGA through Kota Kinabalu
(capital of Sarawak State, East Malaysia)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Once established, there would be immediate opportunities in the
areas of trade and tourism, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
