<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Qualify for Thomas Cup Badminton Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Five-time winners Malaysia
qualified for the final after a hard-won semi-final victory over
runners-up Denmark, with the outcome remaining unclear until after
the final singles match at the 20th Thomas Cup Badminton Finals
here Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia held Denmark to a 2-2 tie on team scores after two
singles and two doubles matches in the semi-final. Denmark's world
eleven Kenneth Jonassen had struggled for 65 minutes before losing
to Malaysia's 29th-ranked Roslin Hashim 1-2.
</P>
<P>
Jonassen became his team's hero Wednesday when he brought
Denmark to a 3-2 victory over China with his come-from-behind win
over world number five Dong Jiong in Group A final match.
</P>
<P>
History seemed to repeat itself Friday when Jonassen had to
play the very same role after Denmark came to a 2-2 tie in the
semi-final against Malaysia, with the 23-year-old Dane, runners-up
in this year's European championships, left facing a match he had
to win to keep his team's title hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
After losing the opening game 15-18, Hashim played a persistent
game in the second, unleashing volleys and smashes which kept the
Dane on the run. The Malaysian took one game back 15-5 in the
second.
</P>
<P>
An impatient Jonassen gradually lost the ground in the decisive
third game and smashed his racket against the floor when he lost
the game 8-15.
</P>
<P>
The match lasted nearly five hours.
</P>
<P>
After a fifth triumph in 1992, Malaysia finished runners-up to
Indonesia in 1994, but failed to reach the last four at the last
world team championships in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In the final of the current championships slated for Sunday
evening, Malaysia will play the winners of another semi-final
Friday evening between defending champions Indonesia and four-time
winners China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
