<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Improving Management of Overseas-funded Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 22 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region has recently issued a set of regulations to
standardize local government departments' management of
overseas-funded businesses.
</P>
<P>
"Regulations on Management of Overseas-Financed Enterprises"
stipulate that economic and trade commissions at different levels
of the region are departments for comprehensive management of
overseas-financed enterprises.
</P>
<P>
These economic and trade commissions are put to be responsible
for project implementation, production situation, solving
difficulties and problems for the overseas-funded enterprises, but
are not allowed to interfere in normal operations of
overseas-funded businesses under the pretext of inspection,
according to the regulations.
</P>
<P>
The regulations stipulate overseas-financed enterprises are
entitled to refuse irrational levies and file their complaints to
economic and trade commissions of higher levels, or even resort to
legal means to safeguard their interests.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, overseas-financed enterprises should
strictly follow registration procedures for starting up businesses
and get preferential tax treatment accordingly upon the documents
of approval in a bid to avoid cheating in investment activities,
said the regulations.
</P>
<P>
Investors of the overseas-financed enterprises are also urged
to strictly observe the terms stated in the signed contracts and
make their due investment as stipulated, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the autonomous region had approved the
establishment of 1,057 overseas-funded enterprises, and 550 of
them had become operational, involving a use of 930 million
U.S. dollars of overseas investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
