<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Shows Smoking Linked to Serious Eye Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Nearly all the serious
ophthalmological diseases, some of which end in blindness, are
significantly worsened by smoking, according to a medical study by
Israeli researchers.
</P>
<P>
Compared to non-smokers, those who smoke are 2.5 times more
likely to develop macular degeneration, an incurable condition
causing full or partial blindness in middle-aged and elderly
people, the study says.
</P>
<P>
After analyzing related studies conducted around the world,
doctors of the Goldschlege Eye Research Institute at Tel Aviv
University concluded that of the 4,000 active substances in
tobacco smoke, many of them are toxic to eye tissues. Their study
was published in this week's Survey Ophthalmology.
</P>
<P>
The doctors also found that smoking is linked with Grave's
disease, which is caused by thyroid problems. Smoking constricts
the blood vessels and reduces the supply of blood to the eye,
making the condition more severe, they said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, pregnant women who smoke increase the risk of
strabismus (crossed eyes) in their babies, the doctors said.
</P>
<P>
In other researches, doctors have found that cataracts, in
which the lens become cloudy and which is the most common
condition causing blindness, has something to do with smoking.
</P>
<P>
As a result, "one must add to the list of smoking warnings the
direct damage smoking causes to the eyes, " said Michael Belkin,
one of the doctors who conducted the study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Boeing 777-300 Delivered to Cathay Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Co., the largest
aircraft maker in the world, Thursday delivered its first 777-300,
the world's longest commercial jet, to an Asian carrier.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific, based in Hong kong, took delivery of the huge
airplane, which is more than 10 feet longer than a 747-400 jumbo
jet and 33 feet longer than the 777-200 that entered service three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the 747-400 carries more passengers -- 420 in three
classes, weighs more and has a larger wingspan than the
777-300. It also flies farther than the 777-300.
</P>
<P>
With lower operating cost, the 777-300 is aimed at replacing
aging 747-200s and 747-300s on medium-length routes, such as the
ones within Asia. Boeing has 53 orders for the 777-300 so far from
eight Asian airlines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
