<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Share prices resumed their fall
on the Singapore market after Thursday's surge, as the benchmark
Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) shed 5.98 points to close
at 1313.67 points on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market eased on worries over whether
Indonesia's problem could be resolved under President B J
Habibie's new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Activity on the exchange slackened after the midday break as
shares gave up their earlier gains, they said, adding that the
market was also in consolidation after the wild gyrations seen
this week.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank to 204.62 million units, valued
at 325.32 million Singapore dollars (198.37 million U.S. dollars).
Declines overwhelmed advances by 240 to 80, while 272 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Telecom was the most actively traded stock as it
registered a turnover of 14.98 million units. It was followed by
Malaysia Resources which had 13.99 million shares traded. Renong
was next with 13.9 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 1.7 Singapore dollars to finish at 33.5
dollars. Tong Meng increased by 1.4 dollars to end at 2.6
Singapore dollars. Asean was up by 90 cents to close at 7.5 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Goodwood was the biggest loser as it declined
by 50 cents to end at 25.5 Singapore dollars. Tan Chong fell by
46.5 cents to close at 61.5 Singapore cents, while NBT was down by
27 cents to finish at 1.77 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
