<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gingrich Says Security Key to Israeli-Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. House of Representatives
Speaker Newt Gingrich reiterated his position on the eve of his
visit to Israel that security concern should be "a critical
consideration" in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has learned from a shared experience with Israel that
"any lasting peace can only rest upon genuine security for those
who seek peace," Gingrich said in an article published on Friday's
Jerusalem Post. "We must support a peace process predicated on
security," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the continued possibility of a conventional
war, Israel today faces "the constant threat of terrorism and the
prospect that terrorist states develop weapons of mass
destruction", Gingrich said, accusing Iran of developing nuclear
technology.
</P>
<P>
In a new round of accusation against the Clinton
administration, Gingrich said that the Israeli security needs must
be defined by Israel alone and should not be determined by "those
who have never faced a threat to their survival."
</P>
<P>
The speaker has recently criticized U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright for being "out of touch with reality" by
trying to pressure Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in
their talks in Washington to accept the U.S. proposal for a
further Israeli redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
In his article, Gingrich also blamed the Palestinian
Liberation Organization for its failure to remove from its
charter the call for Israel's destruction, which he described as
"a major stumbling block in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
The speaker is expected to arrive in Israel this weekend,
together with U.S. House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, to
participate in celebrations marking the 50th anniversary of the
establishment of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Even before his arrival he had already caused controversy by
saying that he would go with Gephardt to visit the proposed site
of the U.S. Embassy in Jerusalem. Senior Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat warned Thursday that Gingrich is "playing with fire"
and could trigger bloodshed by meddling in the Israeli-Palestinian
dispute over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
No issue is more sensitive in the Israeli-Palestinian peace
negotiations than the status of Jerusalem. Israel regards the city
as its capital, a claim only accepted by a number of countries,
while the Palestinians also claim it as the capital of their
future state. The U.S. Congress has ordered that the U.S. embassy
will be moved from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"I urge Mr. Gingrich to resort to sanity, wisdom, and
far-sightedness and not to pour oil on the fire," Erekat said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
