<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Intensifies Efforts to Increase Farmers' Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China is trying every possible
means to increase farmers' income in a bid to develop rural
consumption market as part of the effort to accomplish this year's
economic development goals.
</P>
<P>
Farmers' per-capita net income was 2,080 yuan last year, a
year-on-year rise of 4.6 percent, but dropping from the 9 percent
growth in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Economists attributed the fall to difficulties of farm produce
sales and township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Now, investment, farming infrastructure and industrialization,
township enterprises, and small town construction are top
priorities of the rural work of the government.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural industrialization is the top priority. Hebei
Province, one of the country's major grain producers, for example,
has developed 950 projects for agricultural industrialization,
contributing 30 percent to farmers' income.
</P>
<P>
Jilin Province in northeast China is another example. It plans
to increase 60 billion yuan in agricultural output over the next
five years by way of industrialization, including the formation of
farm produce processing businesses, production bases, imports of
stud bulls, and a project to process a million tons of maize a
year.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of laid-off workers in cities has slowed
down the exodus of rural surplus laborers. So, development of
small towns in rural areas has become a new source to employ
rural laborers and to increase farmers' income.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has 16,000 small towns, and each has
33 township enterprises on average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Life Insurance Company Opening Office in China's Chongqing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Sun Life, the Canadian life
insurance company, has gotten approval from the Chinese government
to open a representative office in the municipality of Chongqing,
it is learnt from the company's representative office in Beijing
today.
</P>
<P>
The company is the first foreign life insurance firm approved
by the Chinese government to open an office in Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
Dale Pounder, a VP of Sun Life International Business, said
that Chongqing has been found to have large growth potential after
having become China's fourth municipality in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Sun Life office there will be responsible for handling the
company's projects in southwest China and helping the Canadian
insurance industry to learn more about the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, which is on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River,
is the largest city in China, with an area of 82,400 square
kilometers and a population of 30 million. It is regarded as a
connection between eastern and western parts of China and an
industrial center for southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Sun Life opened its first China office in Beijing three years
ago. The company has 139.2 billion US dollars in capital and more
than 10 million private and corporate clients in Canada, the
United States, Britain and the Asia-Pacific Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
