<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Opens Financial Sector Wider to Outside (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The recent opening of a branch by
Citibank Corp. of the United States in this provincial capital has
further boosted the upbeat momentum of south China's Guangdong
Province in opening its financial sector to overseas businesses.
</P>
<P>
Confidence in China's long-term political and economic
stability and good prospects prompted Citibank to set up this
branch, according to Stephen Long, Citibank's North-Asia regional
head.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the branch indicated that China, especially the
coastal areas like Guangdong, will continue to open its financial
sector for overseas participation despite the Asian financial
crisis, local analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for the opening of a branch by a Belgian bank are
now in full swing, and another 18 foreign banks and 13 insurance
companies have applied for opening business agencies in the province.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has one of China's most developed market economies,
and is home to a large number of oversease-funded enterprises. And in
recent years, not a few of Citibank's clients have increased
investment in the province, so a branch here is quite necessary
to provide better services, Mr. Long explained.
</P>
<P>
By last year, the province had 121 overseas-backed financial
institutions, accounting for 17 percent of the nation's total, and
those operational (except in Shenzhen) had 3.65 billion US dollars
in total assets, and 43 million US dollars in profits, accounting
for 10 and 17 percent of the national total, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Opens Financial Sector Wider to Outside (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guangdong began to allow overseas financial services in 1981
when a Hongkong-based bank opened a representative office in the
city. And in 1992, Guangzhou was chosen as one of the country's
two pilot cities to open insurance market to overseas companies.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-backed financial organizations play an increasingly
important role in local economic development. The Daya Bay Nuclear
Power Station, for example, was mainly financed by overseas
financial institutions, and some of them also granted loans to
China's Southern Airlines for aircraft purchases.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 85 percent of the 2.9 billion US dollars
of outstanding loans by foreign-funded banking businesses at the
end of last year went to domestic projects, while their deposit
savings that came from China only made up 11 percent of the
outstanding loans.
</P>
<P>
Increased involvement of foreign banks has made it possible for
the province to provide better financial services to 60,000
overseas-funded enterprises in terms of credit loans,
settlements, risk consulting, insurance business, and
creditability investigations.
</P>
<P>
Overseas financial institutions have also brought in advanced
management expertise, money-raising means and, more importantly,
competition, said Xiao Gang, head of a local branch of the
People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong will make greater efforts to open the financial
sector to foreign participation in a bid to promote the sector to
reach the internationally accepted standard, the official added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
