<HEADLINE> Most Parts of S. Leone Safe for Travel: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Most parts of Sierra Leone are now
safe for travel between towns apart from the east and north where
remnants of the ousted junta are reportedly killing and maiming
innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
With the atrocities perpetrated by the rebel forces, people in
the country are worrying about traveling out of cities,
particularly at night.
</P>
<P>
However, a correspondent of the British Broadcasting
Corporation (BBC) found it was quite safe for her to travel from
Bo, the second largest city in the south, to the capital Freetown
Wednesday night, according to a BBC report monitored here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the danger claimed by many local people, the
correspondent met no incident on her way and she even received
aid from the west African peace keeping force (ECOMOG), which is
in charge of the country's security.
</P>
<P>
Instead of safety, what needs to be worried about is the
quality of the road, the report said. Years of civil war and
lack of repair have left the road in a very poor condition.
</P>
<P>
It said the villages along the road are full of life, with
people walking on the street at midnight.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an ECOMOG commander as saying that most
parts of the ECOMOG soldiers at various check-points are very
polite and assistant, checking the car and the booth carefully.
But there is nobody asking for anything as bribe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
