<HEADLINE> Gansu Province Using Rainwater to Cultivate Fruits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Gansu Province in northwest China
has started a pilot project to develop fruit-planting in arid and
semi-arid areas, using rainwater.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.25 million people and 980,000 head of livestock in the
Loess Plateau areas of the province have long been plagued by
serious droughts.
</P>
<P>
Since 1980s, local scientists have speeded up the research of
rainwater irrigation, and developed some practical methods to
collect the rainwater. The most commonly used way is to store
rainwater in wells and then use it whenever needed.
</P>
<P>
By last year, the province had been able to use the stored
rainwater to irrigate nearly 85,000 hectares of dry farmland.
</P>
<P>
Technicians with the province's forestry scientific research
institute also helped farmers develop cottage economy using stored
rainwater. And an increasing number of farmers are participating
in the effort.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
