<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Referendum Held in N.Ireland, Irish Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland and the Irish
Republic began voting on Friday on whether to accept a peace
agreement designed to end 30 years of conflict in Britain's divided
province.
</P>
<P>
Polling stations across Northern Ireland opened on time at
0700 local (0600 GMT) and voting in the Irish Republic started an
hour later, making Friday's ballot the first all-Ireland election
since 1918.
</P>
<P>
The province's 1.18 million voters must answer "Yes" or "No"
to one question on the peace deal, while in the Irish Republic,
2.75 million electors will decide whether to back changes in the
Irish constitution proposed in the agreement. The agreement was
reached last month by eight major political parties in Northern
Ireland after 22-month hard negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The peace deal sets out new arrangements for the internal
administration of Northern Ireland and for new cross-border bodies
designed to improve cooperation between the north and south of
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for changes to the Irish constitution which
alter the Republic's claim to Northern Ireland, so that it talks
of uniting people rather than territory.
</P>
<P>
Latest opinion polls show a majority of voters would back the
peace deal but a significant number of Protestants in Northern
Ireland had still undecided.
</P>
<P>
Electoral officials in Northern Ireland said the early turnout
was "extraordinary high."
</P>
<P>
Final results from both votes are not expected until
Saturday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
