<HEADLINE> South China Tiger Gives Birth To Cub in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A three-year old South China tiger
gave birth to a male baby tiger over the weekend at a zoo in
China's largest metropolis of Shanghai, east China.
</P>
<P>
Being young, inexperienced and without much milk, the young
mother has refused to attend to her baby, leaving it to the hands
of the zoo-keeper Gu Wenyang who has been working in the Shanghai
Zoo for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Though still unable to open his eyes, the cub is said to be
alive and well, with his weight increasing to 1.5 kilograms from
1.15 kg at the time of its birth.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are approximately 50 South China tigers in
China, mostly in zoos. The newly-born tiger cub represents the
sixth generation bred by the Shanghai zoo since 1960s and has
increased the number of south China tiger to eight.
</P>
<P>
However, zoo workers are worrying about the inbreeding of the
animal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
