<HEADLINE> U.S. Jetliner Hits Turbulence over Pacific, 7 Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Seven passengers and crew were
injured Thursday when a U.S. jetliner from Los Angeles to Hawaii hit
clear-air turbulence over the Pacific Ocean, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Two passengers and a 26-year-old steward were seriously injured
when the Continental Airlines DC-10 flight, carrying 285 passengers
and crew, was bounced around by the turbulence about 150 miles off the
California coast, said Mitch Barker, a spokesman for the Federal
Aviation Administration in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
Four others, two flight attendants and two passengers, received
slight injuries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles Fire Dept. spokesman Brian Humphrey said the pilot
advised flight controllers at Los Angeles International Airport that
he was returning to the airport with injured passengers.
</P>
<P>
Paramedics boarded the aircraft when it returned to the airport.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that turbulence is unstable air that can make an
airliner bump, rise and fall. Storm clouds and mountain ranges can
cause it, but there also are invisible, unpredictable areas of
unstable air known as clear-air turbulence, they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
