<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Say El Nino Will End Between July and August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China's National Research Center
for Marine Environmental Forecasts said today that the El Nino
breaking out last year will end between July and August this year.
</P>
<P>
The center's deputy director Song Xuejia said, " The obvious
change of the major indexes of the El Nino beginning from January
1998 indicates its prime time is over, and has been on the wane."
</P>
<P>
Scientists with the center found after long-term monitoring
that the abnormal warm water-body in central and eastern Pacific
Ocean along the equator has been shrinking eastwardly. Meanwhile,
the convection in the Pacific Ocean at the equatorial area has
also been weakening.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing with the sunspot activity cycle, scientists predict
that the El Nino will come to an end in about two months time this
year.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino, the strongest over the last century, has caused
unusual climate in the world, leading to frequent serious natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
"It has also greatly affected China," said Song.
</P>
<P>
Northern China suffered unusual drought last summer, with a
big drop in the production of autumn grain and oil crops and a
record long dry-ups of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Some regions in southern China was flooded, and the Typhoon
Winnie ravaging six provinces and two municipalities in eastern
China caused a loss of more than 50 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China experienced a remarkable warm winter in 1997
because of El Nino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
