<HEADLINE> Heavy Homework Deprives Students' Enjoyable Weekend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Heavy school work has deprived
Chinese students of weekend relaxation and happiness, according to
a survey in Tianjin, a port city in northern China.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by Tianjin Work Committee for Caring
Younger Generation among 2,300 students, 150 teachers and 1,000
parents, finds that 98 percent of the high school students and 92
percent of the elementary school pupils in the city have to spend
most of their weekends doing homework.
</P>
<P>
Apart from school assignments, 35 percent of the high school
students and 44 percent of the elementary school students also
attend various kinds of cram schools or have private tutors, the
survey shows.
</P>
<P>
The students generally have little time to play, the survey
indicates, citing their main weekend pastime as watching TV,
listening to music and playing electronic games.
</P>
<P>
Education experts called for efforts to reduce students' burden
by changing the present exam-oriented educational mode into one
that focuses on fostering students' morality and enhancing
problem-solving capabilities.
</P>
<P>
The whole society should also create conditions to help the
students have a colorful and enjoyable weekend, the experts
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
