<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qinghai Takes Steps to Protect Ecological Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Qinghai Province in northwest China
will increase its financial input into environmental protection,
to the tune of one percent of its economic output, according to a
senior official.
</P>
<P>
It has already worked out a program to strengthen environmental
protection of the Qinghai Plateau, an important component of the
ecological system of the Qinghai-Tibet plateau.
</P>
<P>
The program covers working out environmental protection
policies, law enforcement, land erosion treatment and developing
clean energy.
</P>
<P>
A plan has been worked out to cope with land erosion and
develop ecological agriculture in the province's eastern region,
fight grassland degradation in the southern parts and
desertification of the Qaidam basin, promote afforestation at the
source of the Yangtze River and protect the natural environment of
the Qinghai Lake valley.
</P>
<P>
The natural environment of the Qinghai Plateau has declined due
to intensive human activities, and as much as 330,000 sq km of the
province's land -- 46 percent of the province's total land area --
has been eroded.
</P>
<P>
The severe land erosion has led to a sharp decrease in river
water flow, worsening drought and desertification. One third of
the province's grassland has been degraded, and pollution has been
worsening.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to develop such clean energies as water
power and natural gas. It will build a batch of medium-sized and
small hydro-electric power stations, and explore ways to utilize
wind, solar and subterranean thermal power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps Exploration of Large Oilfields in Bohai Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China is speeding up its efforts to
explore simultaneously two large oilfields in the central part of
the Bohai Bay, in a bid to bring about an annual crude production
capacity of 4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin Shaodong, president of the China Offshore Oil
Bohai Corp (COOBC), crude oil to be turned out by the two
oilfields -- Qinhuangdao 32-6 and Nanbao 35-2, will be piped
inland through the port of Jingtang in Tangshan city, north
China's Hebei province.
</P>
<P>
Qinhuangdao 32-6 Oilfield, with 170 million tons of verified
geological oil reserves, is 100 km east of Tanggu in
Tianjin. Presently, eleven wells have been drilled here.
</P>
<P>
Nanbao 35-2 Oilfield, lies 20 km south of Tangshan. Four test
wells have been drilled and geological reserves of 70 million tons
have been identified. Nanbao's reserves have been estimated at 110
million tons.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the distance between the two oilfields
is just 20 km, making it possible for their joint development in a
70-sq km oil-bearing area in the central Bohai Sea.
</P>
<P>
He said seven standard platforms will be erected in the two
oilfields, two pipelines be laid at the seabed to transport oil
inland, and terminals will be built in Jingtang Port.
</P>
<P>
And requisition of 650 meters of coastline will be made for
building oil transport berths. The entire construction will cost
7.29 billion yuan, he added.
</P>
<P>
The official forecasts that the Qinhuangdao 32-6 Oilfield will
begin production in the year 2003 and Nanbao one year later. By
2004, the two oilfields are expected to produce four million tons
of oil a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
