<HEADLINE> Cholera Under Control in Mozambique: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Avertino Batteto, assistant
director of Mozambique National Health Bureau, has announced that
the cholera epidemic which had been plaguing the country in the
past year, has been brought under control.
</P>
<P>
In the past two days, only 26 were affected by the disease
around the country, but no death was reported, the Noticias
paper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Batteto said here Thursday that Sofala and Zambezia provinces
in central Mozambique were still areas with the most cases, with
12 and 10 people infected by the disease respectively in the past
two days.
</P>
<P>
The official cited less water consumption, full water supply
and improved hygienic conditions as the reason for reduced cases.
</P>
<P>
Cholera broke out first in the capital Maputo last August,
then spread from the south to the north, until eight of the 10
provinces in the country were hit by the epidemic, with a total
of 35,000 people so far contracting the disease and 803 having
died of it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
