<HEADLINE> Burkina Faso Denies Aiding S. Leonean Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Burkina Faso has denied accusations
that it was supporting the remnants of the dislodged military
junta and allied rebels in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"Our people have problems with (lack of) water. With such a
situation, we are not going to find the means to get involved in
a country as far away as Sierra Leone," said the country's
Foreign Minister Ablasse Ouegraogo, quoted by a report reaching
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean refugees, who fled fighting at home, have
accused Burkina Faso of being "the main supplier of arms,
ammunition and food" to die-hard supporters of the junta.
</P>
<P>
Remnants of the junta and allied rebels have fled to the east
and north of Sierra Leone for guerrilla wars since the fall of
the military regime more than three months ago.
</P>
<P>
The west African peace keeping force, which drove the junta
out of the capital Freetown, is now carrying out operations in
northern and eastern Sierra Leone to mop up the anti-government
forces.
</P>
<P>
"Do you think we have the means to support a rebellion with
such financial obligations lying ahead?" Ouegraogo asked,
referring to the forthcoming June summit of the Organization of
African Unity in Ouagadougou, capital of Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, it is intolerable to seek legality
through force in the case of Sierra Leone, one must use dialog.
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps that is the cause of the opposition leveled against
Burkina Faso and Liberia," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
