<HEADLINE> E. Africa to Harmonize Educational Curricula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda, the
three members of the East Africa Cooperation (EAC), will make
join efforts to harmonize their educational curricula,
examinations and certification.
</P>
<P>
The move is in line with the EAC treaty which is expected to
be ratified by the three presidents in November, the Daily Nation
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The three states also intend to strengthen the activities of
the Inter-University Council for East Africa.
</P>
<P>
They have vowed to promote the existing common research and
training institutions and establish new ones to enhance
cooperation in industrial training and in the application of
research and technology.
</P>
<P>
Vocational training programs will be established for adults.
Exchange programs for teachers and students within the community
will be boosted by encouraging recognition of academic diplomas
and periods of study, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The three countries will also put in place education
facilities for people with disabilities and other disadvantaged
groups and improve the existing ones.
</P>
<P>
They will encourage participation of the private sector in the
development of human resources, science and technology and ensure
a conducive environment for it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the use and development of indigenous science and
technology, exchange of scientific information, the promotion and
publication of research findings will also be encouraged.
</P>
</TEXT>
