<HEADLINE> 2 Warring Afghan Factions Trade Fire North of Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia and
the Northern Alliance exchanged heavy shells and mortars early
Friday on frontlines north of the Afghan capital, Kabul.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here from Kabul quoted witnesses as saying
that the rumbling of rocket, artillery and mortar fire was clearly
audible in the Taliban-controlled capital city in the early hours
of Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report quoted local residents as saying that
forces loyal to Ahmad Shah Masoon, defense minister in the ousted
Afghan government, fired at least three heavy rockets into the
Kabul airport early Friday.
</P>
<P>
This was the second rocket assault on the Kabul airport in
recent days by the anti-Taliban forces who say they want to shut
down Kabul's only airfield.
</P>
<P>
There were no immediate reports of casualties or damage in the
strikes.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia, which control Kabul and about 85 percent
of the Afghan territory, have been sending dozens of fighter jets
toward the opposition-held north from the airport in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban Northern Alliance says it wants to close the
airport to stop the bombing of its positions.
</P>
<P>
According to another report from Kabul two Taliban fighter jets
and a cargo plane took off from the Kabul airport after the
rocketing, an indication that the runway was usable.
</P>
<P>
Military conflict in war-torn Afghanistan between the Taliban
and the Northern Alliance has been stepped up following the
collapse of peace talks early this month. The peace talks were
jointly organized by the United Nations and the Organization of
Islamic Conference. 
</P>
