<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lusaka Rakes in $5 Million from House Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Lusaka City Council (LCC) has
raised about 9.2 billion Kwacha (about five million U.S. Dollars)
from the sale of its houses since the exercise began two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Friday quoted Lusaka Mayor Fisho Mwale as
saying Thursday that so far 9,214 houses, almost 60 percent of
the LCC housing stock, have been sold.
</P>
<P>
The money from the sale is being channeled to the housing
re-development fund, which has since released about six billion
Kwacha (about 3.2 million US Dollars) for the construction of 120
houses in the capital city, he said.
</P>
<P>
He complained that some tenants have not shown commitment to
finishing payment for their houses but said the council is
dealing with people facing economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"But that does not mean we will not be tough in order to
ensure that people meet the deadline," he said, adding that
tenants should realize that the houses remain the property of the
council until the money is paid out in full.
</P>
<P>
According to Mwale, the financial base for the LCC is sound
and it is still able to pay out salaries for its employees
despite disposing of its housing stock.
</P>
<P>
Sale of government and council houses to their sitting tenants
is part of Zambia's new housing policy to support home ownership
and make free housing the past. 
</P>
</TEXT>
