<HEADLINE> 12 Killed in Flood in Northwestern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A total of 12 people were killed and
13 others reported missing in a ravage flood hitting the
northwestern Turkish region, TV and newspaper reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Strong rainstorms swept across the provinces of Zonguldak,
Bartin, Karabuk, Bolu, Aydin and Kars on Wednesday and Thursday,
causing an unprecedented flood in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Houses were inundated and many people were forced onto the
roofs to get a shelter. Several major highways were closed due to
landslides and the collapses of several bridges.
</P>
<P>
The 12 deaths were reported in different parts of the region,
and another 179 people surrounded by the flood were still in a
dangerous condition, according to local government officials.
</P>
<P>
In some cities in the region, electricity supplies stopped and
communications with the outside were cut off, making the rescue
work more difficult.
</P>
<P>
Turkish government had set up an emergency commission headed
by Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit to take charge of the
rescue and aid work to the flood-stricken provinces.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Air Force had sent some helicopters
and a transport plane to the region. Soldiers also rushed to the
region.
</P>
<P>
At present, the flood is still rising in many parts of the
region due to the rainfall. The Meteorology General Directorate
announced that the storms would continue in the next few
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
