<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 550,000 Households in Tianjin Owning Apartments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Approximately 550,000 households in
Tianjin, which has a population of nine million, now own their own
apartments, with their combined floor space making up 43.8 percent
of the city's total volume.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 227,000 households in Tianjin
have bought government-subsidized apartments, with the floor space
totaling 14.38 million sq m, and some 323,000 households have
purchased open-market flats or privately-owned houses, with the
combined floor space amounting to 16.72 million sq m, over the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
During the era of planned economy, China had practiced a system
of distributing government-subsidized apartments as a form of
welfare in urban areas, which had long plagued by a difficulty of
not having enough to go round.
</P>
<P>
China has announced the abolishment of the system of
distributing housing in kind and to monetize housing distribution
as a way to reform its housing system in the wake of expanded
market economy. It encourages more residents to buy the
distributed government-subsidized apartments.
</P>
<P>
To urg more households to buy their own apartments, Tianjin
decided to slash taxes for sale of government-subsidized
apartments from 13.3 percent to five percent starting from this
April.
</P>
<P>
The measure enables residents exempting from paying land use
right fees for five years when they buy the resident apartments,
and a 8.3 percent cut in taxes when the residents resell the
apartments. This measure has proved effective, and helps
accelerate the pace for housing reform, said local official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Vows to Bring Inflation Rate Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government has
vowed to further reduce the inflation rate from 15 to 7.5 percent
in the next fiscal year beginning from July.
</P>
<P>
Dar es Salaam newspapers Friday quoted a senior treasury
official as saying that the measures to control inflation
include, avoiding bank borrowing, making repayments to the
banking system, and continuation of cash budgeting which involves
spending the actual revenue received.
</P>
<P>
"These measures are expected to reduce the money supply and
make more credit available to the private sector," Raphael
Mollel, the Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Finance, said
while opening a two-day seminar on monetary policy stance in
Tanzania in the northern region of Arusha Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the measures taken by the government during the
fiscal reforms in 1991, inflation dropped drastically from 38
percent in the early 1990s to 15 percent last July.
</P>
<P>
To enhance efficiency of financial institutions, Mollel noted
that the government, through the Bank of Tanzania (BoT), will
carry out divestiture of the financial institutions and encourage
the entry of new private banks and other financial agencies.
</P>
<P>
On credit problems in rural areas, Mollel said people will be
mobilized to form their own community banks and credit and
service schemes.
</P>
<P>
He also said the liberalization of the insurance sector is
progressing well as two private insurance firms have been
licensed in addition to the state-owned National Insurance
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, attended by 60 senior bankers, has been
organized by the Tanzania Institute of Bankers, with support from
BoT, United States International Development Agency (USAID),
central banks of Uganda, Kenya and the Tanzaoia Banker's
Association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
