<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Halting Environmental Deterioration In Northeastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Jilin Province
has succeeded in bringing 95 percent of the drinking water in
urban areas up to national standards after five years of battling
severe pollution.
</P>
<P>
The province has built 66 facilities in different cities for
more efficient central heating and environmental protection and
has provided natural gas for 300,000 families in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Government departments got rid of 120 sources of industrial
pollution and, by the end of 1997, had treated 74 percent of the
polluted water, according to a senior Environmental Protection
Bureau official.
</P>
<P>
Monitoring has shown that the average amount of suspended
particles in each cubic meter of air is 356 micrograms, 70
micrograms less than in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Jilin has many large state-owned industries and has suffered
from heavy pollution for several decades, but the government
decided in 1990 to try to stop the environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
Jilin also has 35 different nature reserves, which cover ten
percent of the province's land mass, and some cities and counties
are trying out more ecologically-sound agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
