<HEADLINE> Abducted Girls Should Be Freed by Force: Museveni </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has said that the 20 school girls abducted by Kony rebels should
only be freed by force since the rebels refused to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
Museveni made the statement at a press conference jointly held
with Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the failure by the rebels to release the girls on May
14 confirmed he is right to see the use of force as the only way
to rescue them.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan President said he was bluffed into releasing the
42 Sudanese prisoners of war on condition that the Sudanese
government would reciprocate Uganda's goodwill gesture and
release the girls being held by Joseph Kony's rebels since 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Lord Resistance Army (LRA), spearheaded by Joseph Kony, is
a rebel group in northern Uganda and it usually retreats into
southern Sudan when faced with mounting pressure from the Ugandan
army. The rebels killed and abducted in the northern districts
like Kitgum and Gula, posing a potential threat to the security
of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The girls were abducted by the LRA from St. Mary's school, at
Aboke on October 9, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The rebels initially abducted 130 girls, but the school's
deputy headmistress, an Italian Roman Catholic nun, Rachele
Fassera, followed them into the bush and persuaded the rebel
commander to free all but 30, who were retained allegedly for
their beauty.
</P>
<P>
Nine of the girls have since escaped, while one was killed by
the rebels last year when she tried to get out of rebels' hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
