<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Everything Ready for HK's First Post-handover Legislative Council Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Feng Xiuju, Tao Wenge
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Everything is ready for Sunday's
election of the first Legislative Council of Hong Kong after it
became a Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China last July.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2.8 million registered voters are expected to cast
their votes to choose from 166 candidates the 60 members of the
Legislative Council from 7:30 a.m. to 10:30 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Legislative Council Ordinance, of the 60
Legislative Council members, 20 are to be returned from the
geographical constituencies, 30 from the functional constituencies
and 10 from the Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 500 polling stations are set up across Hong Kong
following the month-long publicity activities ranging from roving
exhibitions, advertisements, parades and carnivals to a string of
forums for the candidates to explain their views.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR government has attached great importance to the
legislature election as an important step in fully implementing
the principle of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" with a
high degree of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the HKSAR was founded last July, the Provisional
Legislative Council adopted the Legislative Council Ordinance in
accordance with the relevant provisions of the Basic Law, drawing
up specific methods for the election of the first HKSAR
Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa appointed a 3-member Electoral
Affairs Commission with Justice Woo Kwok-hing as its chairman, to
supervise the entire election process.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure the election to be conducted in an open,
fair and honest manner, the government formulated the guidelines
on election-related activities in respect of the election after
soliciting opinions from people in all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts made the related activities for the
legislature election orderly and smooth.
</P>
<P>
They included voter registration, the nomination of candidates
for the Election Committee subsector election and the subsector
election of the 800-strong Election Committee as well as the
nomination of candidates for the legislature election.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government has urged the local media to supervise
the election and set up hotlines to receive complaints from local
residents.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Affairs Commission opened two polling stations
Friday, two days ahead of the election, offering local residents
chances to visit them in a bid to increase transparency.
</P>
<P>
On the polling day Sunday, 15,000 civil servants will be
mobilized to assist the election at the polling stations and the
central counting station. Visitors and journalists are allowed to
view the entire process of vote counting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
