<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Public Sector Booming in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The non-public sector in east
China's Fujian Province has experienced fast expansion in recent
years to become an important part of the province's economy.
</P>
<P>
Fujian had 88,000 non-public economic entities by the end of
last year, with their industrial output value and retail sales
standing at 40 and 55.9 percent of the provincial totals,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's non-public sector, which includes private firms,
shareholding entities supported mainly by private funds and
partnership entities, is among the most developed in China. It has
become an important driving force behind Fujian's economic growth
since the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the industrial output value of
Fujian's non-public sector grew an average 49.4 percent between
1991 and 1997. The rate is 17.9 percentage points higher than the
growth rate for the entire industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, the non-public sector turned in 2.35
billion yuan in industrial and commercial taxes last year. The
figure is up 23.6 percent from 1996 and 12.3 percent of the
province's total tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's non-public sector, which covers electronics,
machinery, chemicals, computer, agriculture, fishery, building
materials, biological engineering and energy, has absorbed a huge
number of eligible and displaced workers in recent years. Its
workforce had reached more than 3.6 million employees by the end
of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder (1): Political Structure in HKSAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The political structure of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of the People's
Republic of China (PRC) consists of three major parts -- the Chief
Executive and the Executive Authorities, the Legislature and the
Judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive is the head of the HKSAR, who is
accountable to the Central People's Government of the PRC and the
HKSAR. The Chief Executive serves a term of five years in office.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive is also the head of the government of the
HKSAR, which is the Executive Authorities of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
A Department of Administration, a Department of Finance, a
Department of Justice, and various bureaus, divisions and
commissions are established in the government of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Justice of the HKSAR controls criminal
prosecutions, free from any interference.
</P>
<P>
An Executive Council is established as an organ for assisting
the Chief Executive in policy making. Members of the Executive
Council are appointed by the Chief Executive from among the
principal officials of the Executive Authorities, members of the
Legislative Council and public figures.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Council of the HKSAR is the Legislature of the
Region.
</P>
<P>
The first Legislative Council of the HKSAR are formed through
election on May 24, 1998. Of the 60 members, 20 are returned
through direct election in geographical constituencies, 30 are
chosen through functional constituencies and 10 are elected by the
800-strong Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
The courts of the HKSAR at all levels are the Judiciary of the
HKSAR, exercising the judicial power.
</P>
<P>
The power of final adjudication of the HKSAR is vested in the
Court of Final Appeal of the Region. The courts of the HKSAR
exercise judicial power independently, free from any interference.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder (2): Hong Kong Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong, a small region of less
than 1,100 square kilometers inhabited by six million people, has
developed into an economic powerhouse despite its lack of natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong economy has nearly quadrupled over the past two
decades, with its GDP growing at an average annual rate of about
seven percent in real terms. The World Bank has ranked Hong Kong's
per capita GDP, in terms of purchasing power parity, the sixth
highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong holds the world's third largest foreign exchange
reserves, after Japan and China's mainland. Its foreign currency
assets totaled 92.8 billion U.S. dollars at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
As a small and open economy, Hong Kong's economic success owes
a great deal to the remarkable performance of its external trade
sector.
</P>
<P>
It is the world's seventh largest trading economy, and the U.S.
Heritage Foundation has named Hong Kong the freest economy in the
globe four years in a row.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has established itself as a major international
financial center. It is the world's fifth largest banking center
in terms of the volume of external banking transactions, and the
fifth largest foreign exchange market in terms of turnover. Its
stock market is Asia's second largest in terms of market
capitalization and ranks the seventh in the world. Hong Kong is
also the world's fourth largest gold bullion market.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has emerged as Asia's services hub, with exports of
services ranging from accounting and legal services, to insurance
and fund-raising, and telecommunications and media.
</P>
<P>
Low tax rates, a level-playing field, rule of law, clean
government, free flow of information, free market competition, and
 efficient infrastructure have all contributed to the success of
Hong Kong economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Financial Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is a major
international financial center, thanks to its favorable
geographical position, bridging the time gap between North America
and Europe, and its strong links with the Chinese inland areas and
other parts of Asia.
</P>
<P>
The absence of any restriction on capital flows is also an
important factor for the growth of the Hong Kong financial
industry.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the world's fifth largest banking center in terms
of the volume of external banking transactions. It has a very
strong presence of international institutions. Some 500 banks and
deposit-taking companies from 43 countries and regions have
operations here, including 82 of the world's top 100 banks.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has a mature and active foreign exchange market,
which ranks the fifth in the world and forms an integral part of
the global market.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the world's fourth largest gold bullion market.
Its stock market is Asia's second largest in terms of market
capitalization and ranks the seventh in the world. The stock
market acts as an important funding source for companies in Asia,
particularly for those Chinese enterprises seeking overseas
investment.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's derivative market is among Asia's largest,
reflecting the increased sophistication of its financial markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
