<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebei Province Regulates Property Rights Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei province
recently worked out a set of rules on the transfer of state-owned
property rights to regulate the nascent market.
</P>
<P>
The rules have detailed stipulations on property rights
transfer authorization, qualifications for intermediary agencies
involved in property rights transfer, the property rights transfer
procedure, the use of proceeds from property rights transfer,
property rights transfer supervisions, and punishment for rule
violators.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Hebei has issued certificates to qualified property
rights transfer agencies and launched qualification tests among
property rights transfer professionals.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that Hebei's property rights
turnover exceeded 1.7 billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
As China moves from a planned to a market economy, property
rights transfers have become increasingly frequent. Besides Hebei,
many other provinces and municipalities have also set up property
rights transfer centers and formulated rules to regulate the
rapidly-expanding market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 800,000 Beijingners Work in Private Sector Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Some 800,000 laid-off workers in
Beijing have been hired in private businesses, which observers
here attribute to booming private sector and the people's changing
concepts on employment.
</P>
<P>
Information supplied by the municipal labor market shows that
during the first season of the year, applicants for posts in
private sector account for 15 percent of the total, for the first
time surpassing the demand percentage, which stood at 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
A latest policy issued by the municipal bureau of labor shows
that the municipal government continues to encourage private
enterprises absorbing job-hunters.
</P>
<P>
Local regulations show that private enterprises which enroll a
certain percentage of laid-off workers are entitled to enjoy such
preferential policies as tax reduction and favorable loans.
</P>
<P>
Any private enterprise which employs a male laid-off worker
above 40 or a female laid-off above 35 and fulfil a two-year
contract with the worker is endowed to receive 4,000 to 6,000 yuan
as re-settlement fees.
</P>
<P>
You Lantian, director of the municipal bureau of labor, said
that private enterprises have been playing a major role in
absorbing laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, sources from the Beijing Municipal Association of the
Self-employed show that the city's private businesses absorbed a
total of 11,000 laid-off workers last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
