<HEADLINE> Multinational Corporations Invest More in Fujian Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Multinational corporations
significantly increased their investment in east China's Fujian
Province in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Investment by companies from developed European countries, the
United States and Japan surged more than 30 percent in the first
three months, official statistics indicate.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-six of the world's largest multinational corporations
have invested in 58 projects in Fujian, with investment totaling
more than five billion US dollars. Of the projects, 26 are in
Xiamen, a special economic zone on the eastern coast.
</P>
<P>
Fujian has been one of the most successful in using overseas
investment since China launched its market economic reform in the
late 1970s. It had approved 23,300 overseas-funded enterprises by
the end of March this year, with contracted overseas investment
reaching 50.64 billion US dollars. The amount of paid-in
investment in Fujian, at 22.89 billion US dollars, is 10 percent
of the national figure.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Hong Kong, Taiwan and southeast Asian countries put
in nearly 80 percent of the overseas investment in
Fujian. However, companies from these places have invested mainly
in small and labor-intensive projects.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Fujian has stepped up its efforts to attract
funds from multinational corporations in developed countries such
as the United States and Japan, according to Vice Governor Cao
Degai.
</P>
<P>
To this end, Fujian has invested more than 30 billion yuan to
improve its infrastructures and train local workers, he added.
</P>
<P>
As the investment environment improves, more multinational
corporations have come to explore investment opportunities in
Fujian.
</P>
<P>
Multinational corporations showing up in Fujian include
Boeing, General Electric, Shell and Matsushita Electric.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
