<HEADLINE> Northern Chinese City Combatting Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Officials in the old Chinese city of
Xi'an have declared war on their increasingly serious air
pollution problem.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an has spent 4.7 billion yuan (about 566 million
U.S. dollars) on environmental protection facilities like a
natural gas pipe project and a large sewage treatment plant.
</P>
<P>
Recent Environment Monitoring Center statistics show Xi'an to
be one of the most seriously polluted provincial capitals in
China. Major pollutants are suspended particles, sulfur dioxide,
and nitrogen oxide.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an is the largest city in this part of China and, under the
name Chang'an, was the capital of eleven dynasties from the
Western Zhou (1100-771 B.C.) to the Tang (618-907 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
Local officials ordered the use unleaded gasoline, and the
natural gas system will be available for another 320,000 urban
families this year.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an has also gotten people to plant shelter belts to help
deal with the dust from the loess plateau to try to get the the
blue sky to return to the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
