<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Malaysia's Bid to Make NPLs Perform Aims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government's
move to set up an asset management company (AMC) to buy out and
manage bank's non-performing loans (NPLs) to make NPLs perform is
a measure that could restore confidence in the banking sector and
expedite the economic recovery process, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim announced
Wednesday the setting up of the (AMC) to take over the NPLs and
troubled assets of the nation's banks to clean up their balance
sheets.
</P>
<P>
Under the mechanism, the nation's banks would be able to write
down the NPLs and sell them to the AMC at depreciated values,
which would manage and try to maximize the recovery of the assets
and thereafter sell them off at market prices.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, promised the AMC, which is
expected to operate within two weeks, would be managed by the
local private sector and international companies and would operate
within the market mechanism without intervention from the
government.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector in Malaysia has been made vulnerable by an
increase in NPLs since the financial crisis hit the region
including Malaysia last July.
</P>
<P>
The NPLs of the banking system in the country increased from
24.04 billion ringgit (about 6.41 billion U.S. dollars) or 5.7
percent of the total loans as at the end of 1997 to about 37.2
billion ringgit (about 9.92 billion U.S. dollars) or 9.3 percent
of the total loans given out as at the end of March this year,
according to official estimates.
</P>
<P>
It was unofficially predicted that the NPLs of Malaysia's
banking system, which once reached a high of 30.1 percent of the
total loans at the end of 1988, might increase to 72-80 billion
ringgit (about 19.2- 21.33 billion U.S. dollars) or 18 to 20
percent of the total loans by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the rising NPLs, most banks saddled with NPLs
and troubled assets have had to make huge provisions, which in
the process curbs their lending capacities.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the NPLs problem has been seen by analysts and
economists as critical in efforts to restore confidence in the
banking system and in the economy in general.
</P>
<P>
With the AMC target clearly stated, the banks in the country
could be relieved from the burden of managing the NPLs and
troubled assets by converting the idle assets into cash to start
off with a clean balance sheet, therefore allowing them to
concentrate on their daily operations.
</P>
<P>
The analysts said an effect of this is that the banks will have
more confidence in giving out badly-needed loans to productive
sectors of the economy and increased lending will help spur the
economy.
</P>
<P>
However, Anwar said that although banks would now be able to
focus on loan disbursements after the setting up of the AMC, the
credit growth target of 15 percent this year would not be reviewed
upwards.
</P>
<P>
And as the move is timely in strengthening the foundation of
banks, the analysts said investors would then look at the banking
sector favorably with more foreign direct investment expected to
flow back to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The setting up of the AMC is not a measure taken in isolation
but is part of a series of measures Malaysia has taken since last
October to revive its economy and restore investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
The various measures and policies taken by the Malaysian
government in view of the tough economic environment included the
austerity measures announced in the 1998 Budget last October, the
cutback in the expenditure in December and the stabilization
measures to consolidate the financial sector taken in March this
year.
</P>
<P>
Optimistic of the latest measure to help generate business
activities and speed up economic recovery and restore confidence,
the analysts did not forget to caution the market against putting
too high expectation for the move to immediately help banks get
rid of their NPLs. They said the AMC alone could not be expected
to make everything all right. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
