<HEADLINE> hke052229 - Indian Home Minister Accused of Creating War Hysteria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- India's opposition parties and
noted figures have accused Home Minister L. K. Advani of creating
war hysteria against Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Advani in his recent strong worded statements linked India's
nuclear capability with the Kashmir issue and threatened to go
pro-active against Pakistan "misadventures."
</P>
<P>
"They are trying for an escalation of tension with the
neighbors," The Hindustan Times quoted Congress leader Ms. Ambica
Soni as saying here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The BJP-led government was trying to whip up a war hysteria to
cover up its internal problems and lack of governance, she said.
</P>
<P>
"No sane person would say that we've got a bomb, we can settle
the Kashmir issue," said H. Singh Surjeet, general secretary of
the Communist Party of India (Marxism) (CPI-M).
</P>
<P>
The provocative statements would only serve to isolate India
diplomatically, he said adding that Advani was definitely trying
to whip up a war hysteria.
</P>
<P>
"This will only lead to a nuclear arms race in the region, or
make the sub-continent more susceptible to a nuclear umbrella from
outside. Either way, it is harmful, said A. B. Bardhan, general
secretary of the Communist Party of India (CPI).
</P>
<P>
Shock, disgust and anger marked the range of reactions of a
cross-section of eminent personalities in the Capital to the
statement of Home Minister Advani that India had decided on a
pro-active response to the Pakistani "misadventures" on its
territory, The Hindustan Times said.
</P>
<P>
Former President of the People's Union for Civil Liberties
Rajindar Sachar said that the saber-rattling by Advani was most
deplorable. "Pokhran 11 (nuclear tests) should have brought
humility and serious introspection. Instead, the BJP shows
arrogance and adventurism," he said.
</P>
<P>
Social activist Prakash Panigrahi said that by behaving like a
regional bully, a wrong message was being given to the
international community. The display of voyeuristic nationalism
soon after conducting the nuclear tests was a diplomatic setback
for India.
</P>
<P>
Peace activist Shabnam Hashmi said that the government was
trying to raise issues which were not real. "For the last 40 years
we have been trying for better relations with our neighbors and
this statement is detrimental to it," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
