<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Information Technology Workers in U.S. Highly Paid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Information technology
professionals are in big demand in the United States and their
salaries are soaring to record levels, according to a recent
survey.
</P>
<P>
About 11,000 respondents to an online survey conducted by
InformationWeek Research said that over the past 12 months, they
have seen their salaries climb by an average of 11 percent, a rate
well above the average of other professions.
</P>
<P>
This is amazing, said InformationWeek, considering that
inflation is low and typical workers in other fields have seen
their paychecks increase by a paltry 3 percent to 4 percent this
past year -- a quarter of what information technology
professionals receive.
</P>
<P>
"Until there is a greater supply of information technology
people, the demand will continue to drive up competition for
talent, compensation and other perks," said Harrs Miller,
president of the Information Technology Association of America, an
industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
Programmers claim the biggest annual percentage gain in base
annual salary, 14.3 percent, while the smallest increase, 7.6
percent, is going to operations managers.
</P>
<P>
Job titles figure greatly in the salaries paid. On average,
directors of information service and information technology earn
79,000 dollars a year, while a chief information officer (CIO)
earns 40,000 dollars more. It's not uncommon for some CIOs,
especially in some large companies, to command salaries of 400,000
to 500,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Demand for people to fix the year 2000 problem as well as to
develop client-server applications such as enterprise resource
planning have made the past year a lucrative one for
programmers. They experienced the biggest pay gains among
information technology professionals. The average annual salary of
a programmer now approaches 58,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Information technology professionals also get an additional 18
percent of compensation from nonsalary perks, including
bonuses. Top executives may get as high as 26 percent of their
compensation from other benefits, such as stock.
</P>
<P>
Some of the more unusual perks to keep information technology
happy include long weekends, extra vacation time and free trips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
