<HEADLINE> U.S. Immigration Commissioner Defends Its Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Commissioner of the
U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) Doris Meissner
Thursday defended the troubled agency against critics in Congress
who want it dismantled.
</P>
<P>
Taking the agency apart "will only divide the problems, not
solve them," Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
"Improving accountability is the key. And we simply cannot
improve accountability by dispersing important functions into
different agencies with different priorities, procedures and
leadership," she told the House Judiciary subcommittee on
immigration and claims.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to stop efforts to split the INS apart, the
Clinton administration has proposed a plan to separate its
operations while keeping the 29,000-person agency intact.
</P>
<P>
Separate staffs with distinct chains of command would be in
charge of the enforcement and service operations, although both
would remain under the control of INS headquarters. They would
have separate offices, but would share access to INS databases and
technologies.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a special immigration commission recommended
abolishing the agency and distributing its functions among the
departments of State, Justice and Labor.
</P>
<P>
Representative Harold Rogers, a Republican and chairman of the
House Appropriations Subcommittee that funds the INS, is
sponsoring legislation to enact the bipartisan commission's
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Rogers' bill would create an agency to police the borders and
find and deport illegal immigrants, put the State Department in
charge of processing immigrant benefits, require the Department of
Labor to find illegal aliens in the workplace, and consolidate
review procedures into an independent agency.
</P>
<P>
Meissner criticized the multiple-agency approach, saying the
INS' functions are too interconnected to be spread across
government.
</P>
<P>
Representative Silvestre Reyes, a Democrat, also criticized the
INS, saying that more than five million illegal immigrants live in
the country while more than two million legal immigrants await
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
"For far too long the U.S. border has been neglected and we are
now paying the price for that neglect," said Reyes, who has
sponsored a separate INS reorganization bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
