<HEADLINE> Air Service Resumed Between Yugoslavia, Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A passenger airplane of Bosnian
airlines Thursday landed on the Belgrade airport, marking the
resumption of air services between Sarajevo and Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
This was the first airliner to have arrived in Belgrade from
Sarajevo since the disintegration of the former Yugoslavia in 1992
which was followed by the Bosnia-Herzegovina civil war. The war
ended at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
A Bosnia-Herzegovina government economic delegation, headed by
Transport Minister Kemal Bubalo, was welcomed by his Yugoslav
counterpart Dejan Drobnjakovic at the airport, according to
Yugoslavia's Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers expressed their belief that the air services
would push forward cooperation between the two countries in
economic and other fields.
</P>
<P>
Under a bilateral agreement, Yugoslav airliners will land in
Sarajevo and Banjaluka, while Bosnian flights will serve the
routes to Belgrade and Podgorica. 
</P>
