<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Most Americans Support Nuclear Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A new poll, taken after India
detonated five underground nuclear explosions last week, shows
that most Americans support the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT).
</P>
<P>
The poll, carried out by the Mellman Group for the private
Coalition to Reduce Nuclear Dangers, showed 73 percent of 1,000
respondents thought the treaty should be ratified by the
U.S. Senate while 16 percent opposed and 11 percent had no view.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was submitted to the Senate last year after
U.S. President Bill Clinton signed it in 1996. But the Senate has
taken no action so far.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Republican Senator Jesse Helms, chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said that he would block a
Senate vote on the treaty, arguing that the Indian tests showed
the accord was "scarcely more than a sham."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration strongly supports the ratification
even though India and its rival Pakistan have not signed the
treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
