<HEADLINE> Dutch Bank Okays Stake-Holding in Thai Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The management of the
Netherlands-based Abn Amro Bank has approved plans to take a 75
percent stake in Thailand's Bank of Asia, the Bangkok Post
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in March, Abn Amro agreed to pay 7.5 billion baht
(192.3 million U.S. dollars) for 1.423 billion new shares in Bank
of Asia, or 75 percent of the bank's total stake. The money are
expected to be paid in July.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the Dutch Bank will purchase a second lot of
10,000 shares in 2000, with prices based on Bank of Asia's asset
value and price-to-book values for the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
After the approval from the Abn Amro's managing board, the deal
now awaits the completion of legal documentation and approval by
regulators and Bank of Asia shareholders.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Asia Chairman Chavalit Thanachanan said the success of
the deal reflected foreign investor confidence in the government's
economic policies and the nation's future prospects.
</P>
<P>
He said Bank of Asia would focus on expanding its mid-level
retail base, aiming for a 5 percent market share within 3-5 years,
from the present share of 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ton de Boer, Abn Amro's Asia Pacific chief executive officer,
said the transaction had so far moved very smoothly.
</P>
<P>
He said the Dutch Bank is now concentrating on how to develop
Bank of Asia's business in Thailand over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Asia is Thailand's 11th largest bank, with 2,300 staff
and 110 branches nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
