<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Launches Space Day 1998 Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Amid crowds of eager children,
Senator John Glenn, the first U.S. astronaut to orbit the Earth,
launched Space Day 1998 celebrations here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Venturing into space has not only served to expand our
knowledge. It has also helped to promote peace and foster
international cooperation," said Glenn.
</P>
<P>
"Young students represent our future space pioneers -- the men
and women of the next generation who will one day help to expand
our frontiers and realize possibilities that my colleagues and I
can only imagine," he said.
</P>
<P>
Through "space age" technology, millions of children around the
globe participated in Space Day celebrations.
</P>
<P>
The centerpiece of this year's celebrations is an eight-hour
Cyber Webcast, broadcast live from the lawn outside the
Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum.
</P>
<P>
A special program during the Webcast was the voice of astronaut
Andy Thomas from the Russian Space Station, Mir, encouraging
students to embrace space and fulfill the visions of space
pioneers.
</P>
<P>
Many visiting children also got the chance to experience the
thrill of a shuttle blast-off during simulated missions aboard
Project Dream Mission, a 63-foot long interactive replica of the
space shuttle which made its debut here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 500,000 students in schools across the United States
and 21 other countries took part in a unique program named
"Students' Signatures in Space." These signatures will be flown
with John Glenn as he is aboard the Shuttle Discovery on the STS95
mission scheduled in October.
</P>
<P>
Space Day is a day dedicated to the extraordinary achievements,
benefits and opportunities in the exploration and use of space.
</P>
</TEXT>
