<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Technology Does Away with Cables </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Personal computers must be
connected to a printer via cable, but a new technology is planning
to change that.
</P>
<P>
Ericsson, IBM, Intel and other companies have unveiled their
vision to revolutionize wireless connectivity for personal and
business mobile devices.
</P>
<P>
The companies will work together to create Bluetooth, the
codename for a short-range radio link to exchange information,
enabling effortless wireless connectivity between mobile phones,
mobile PCs, handheld computers and other peripheral items of
equipment. The radio will operate on the globally available
2.45-GHz "free-band," allowing international travelers to use
Bluetooth enabled equipment worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Bluetooth will eliminate the need for business travelers to
purchase or carry numerous, often proprietary cables, by allowing
multiple devices to communicate with each other through a single
port. Enabled devices will not need to remain within
line-of-sight, and can maintain an uninterrupted connection when
in motion, or even when placed in a pocket or briefcase.
</P>
<P>
The companies said that Bluetooth technology adoption is
expected to be widespread throughout the computer and
telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
With the technology, they said, users will be alerted to, and
can respond to, incoming e-mail via their mobile phone, even while
their mobile PC remains in its carrying case. When the PC receives
an e-mail message, an alert will sound on the mobile phone. It is
then possible to browse incoming e-mails immediately, reading the
contents on the display of the mobile phone.
</P>
<P>
Users will also be able to access the Internet via a completely
wireless connection. They could send an "instant postcard" by
cordlessly connecting a camera to a mobile phone or any wire-bound
connection. They also could add comments to their snapshots using
a mobile phone or mobile PC, and send them instantly to recipients
anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
The first products using the wireless port are expected by the
second half of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
