<HEADLINE> World Bank Assists Health Sector Reform in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved Thursday
interest-free credit worth 90 million U.S. dollars to assist a
health sector reform project in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The project is intended to improve the population's health
status, ensure equity of physical and financial accessibility for
all groups, improve the efficiency and quality of services, and
promote the system's long-term financial sustainability.
</P>
<P>
It is designed to reduce infant mortality from 38 per 1000 to
29 per 1000, under-five mortality from 84 per 1000 to 64 per 1000,
and deaths of women due to pregnancy and delivery from 160 per
100,000 to 90 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be channeled through the International
Development Association, the World Bank's concessional lending
wing for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the second largest recipient of U.S. aid after
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
