<HEADLINE> Remains of Two More Chinese Found at Site of Japanese Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Local people recently
uncovered the remains of two more of the victims of the invading
Japanese army in the 1940s in China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
According to historical records, the Japanese armed forces
massacred 1,280 people in Luannan County on December 5, 1942.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has listed the site of the killing as
an important patriotic education site in recent times.
</P>
<P>
The newly uncovered bodies of a woman and a child are just a
small part of the victims who are still buried, one old survivor
of the horror says. He estimates that more than 100 people are
still buried in that corpse pit.
</P>
<P>
The heads of the two had been cut off, and buttons, pieces of
hair, and ID cards were scattered around the site. 
</P>
</TEXT>
