<HEADLINE> Georgia To See Abkhazia Refugees Returned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Georgia will arrange for refugees to
return to the breakaway region of Abkhazia through talks and other
means, Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze said Thursday in
Tbilisi, capital of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said Shevardnadze made the remarks at the
country's Security Commission meeting held on the worsening
situation in the Gali region.
</P>
<P>
No matter what objection the Abkhaz separatists took, Georgia
would restore its territorial integrity, Shevardnadze said. The
refugees would certainly return to Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, a statement released by the Russian Defense
Ministry said Russian peacekeepers were stationed along the
borders to separate the sides. It called for political measures as
an acceptable way to prevent bloody conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Ministry Spokesman Vladimir Rakhmania said
Thursday that Russia would do its best to push for talks between
Shevardnadze and Abkhaz leader Vladislav Ardzinba. It hoped these
could help normalize the situation in the Gali region.
</P>
<P>
Abkhaz police and forces supporting Georgia have fired on each
other in the Gali region, which lies on the front line between
Abkhaz forces and the Georgian army, bringing about some deaths
and injuries. 
</P>
