<HEADLINE> Central Chinese City Got More Projects In 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Wuhan Technology Development Zone
in the capital of central China's Hubei Province had a total of
790 projects, with an investment of 30.4 billion yuan (3.67
billion US dollars), by the end of 1997, according to a municipal
government official.
</P>
<P>
Its industrial output in first quarter of this year has been
1.13 billion yuan, a 65 percent rise from the same period in
1997. It has 116 foreign-backed projects, with 2.6 billion yuan in
investment, accounting for 71.2 percent of its total
investment. It also has 75 overseas-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Li Xiansheng, Wuhan's vice-mayor, said that, as a central
Chinese hub, Wuhan has become more attractive to foreign
investors. The Dongfeng-Citroen Automobile Co. Ltd., a joint
venture of the China Dongfeng Automobile Company and France's
Citroen, which is a major project in the province, for example,
had an annual production capacity of 30,000 cars, and sales of
28,000 cars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
To improve its investment conditions, Wuhan improved
infrastructure by putting 2.21 billion yuan into water, power, and
other services.
</P>
<P>
After seven years of development, the zone has more than 10
billion yuan (1.2 billion US dollars) in fixed assets, and last
year had 7.1 billion yuan (855 million US dollars) in industrial
output, and 287 million yuan (34.6 million US dollars) in
revenue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
