<HEADLINE> Tianjin Residents Spending Less On Food, Clothing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The residents of the northern
Chinese city of Tianjin have been spending more on housing,
medical care and thing other than food and clothing, a recent
study has shown.
</P>
<P>
Local people had quarterly incomes of 1,829 yuan (220
U.S. dollars) on average, an increase of 8.4 percent over the same
period of last year, the study found.
</P>
<P>
Spending on food accounted for 46.1 percent of total
expenditures in the first three months of 1998, down from 50.2
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
On average, Tianjin residents spend 161 yuan on clothing, ten
percent less than last year, but cultural activities and
entertainment are up 58 percent and housing and medical
expenditures also saw big increases.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the study indicates a healthy spending trend
for the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
