<HEADLINE> Dagestani Authorities, Gunmen Reach Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 21 (Xinhua) -- After several hours of negotiations,
the authorities in the Russian Caucasus republic of Dagestan
Thursday reached a deal with gunmen loyal to a Moslem leader,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The authorities promised not to prosecute the gunmen, who
seized the main government building in the capital Makhachkala
early Thursday. One policeman died and several others were injured
in earlier clashes.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen had withdrawn from the government building and Lenin
Square was under police control.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen were supporters of Nadirshah Khachilayev, head of
the Russian Union of Moslems and a deputy in the Russian Duma
(lower house of parliament).
</P>
<P>
The Kremlin moved quickly to try to defuse the crisis.
President Boris Yeltsin set up an emergency headquarters and
recalled Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin from Strasbourg to
Moscow to take command.
</P>
<P>
Dagestan, a mainly Moslem republic, lies between Chechnya and
the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
The republic of two million people is strategically important
for Russia. Makhachkala is Russia's only year-round, ice-free port
on the Caspian, and a vital transit point for road and rail
traffic and oil exports going north from Azerbaijan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
