<HEADLINE> Ukraine Proposes Pan-European Security System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A pan-European security system should
be established on the basis of the existing security organizations
in the region, Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma told the
Ukrainian Interfax news agency Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new system could be built around the transformed North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), the Euro-Atlantic Partnership
Council (EAPC) and an enlarged European Union (EU), he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Ukraine and NATO were cooperating in military affairs and
techniques; and conducting active political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He said collaboration with NATO was important for Ukraine in
the elimination of technological disasters such as the Chernobyl
accident, scientific research, the exchange of information,
military reforms, and the training of military officers.
</P>
<P>
He believed Ukraine was also strengthening its security
and making significant contributions to the consolidation of
regional stability while cooperating with NATO.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation, he stressed, was not aimed against other
countries and Russia's geo-political interests were also taken
into account.
</P>
<P>
The president emphasized that neither NATO nor Ukraine had ever
raised the issue of Ukraine joining the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma made the address before meeting Suleyman Dimirel,
president of Turkey, a NATO member, who arrived here Thursday on a
visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
