<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs from Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Software piracy in Argentina caused a tax loss
of about 100 million U.S. dollars 1997 alone, said a report
jointly issued by the Chamber of Software Firms and the Legal
Software Company.
</P>
<P>
Naming Argentina as one of the countries with the highest rate
of software piracy in Latin America, the report said individual
customers, as well as small and medium enterprises, are the major
infractors who prefer installing pirate software to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The Inter-American Development Bank has approved an
eight million dollar loan to boost the modernization and
decentralization of the Venezuelan administration at the level of
the central government, as well as for three states of the country.
</P>
<P>
The credit has a 17 year maturity period with three years'
grace, as well as a variable rate of interest, which now is 6.99
percent.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Bancomer Financial Group (GFB) has become
Mexico's number one bank after a successful acquisition of Banca
Promex for the price of 1.78 billion peso (210 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new GFB will boast 1,736 branch offices and more than 3,000
automatic cashiers across the country.
</P>
<P>
The GFB general manager, Ricardo Guajardo Touche, said when the
integration is completed, the Bancomer assets and liabilities will
grow a little more than 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
The total portfolio will grow almost 14 percent and deposits
will increase 19.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- A new oil field found in Colombia by the
United States "GHK" oil company will produce 20,000 barrels of
crude starting next year.
</P>
<P>
The oil field is located near Guaduas in the department of
Cundinamarca, where two wells have been drilled.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian Oil Company (Ecopetrol) will announce soon the
marketing of the field which has minimum estimated reserves of 100
million barrels.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's exports in the first four months of this
year increased 7.7 percent from the same period last year, said a
report of the Brazilian Industry, Commerce and Tourism Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured goods which enjoyed an increase in exports were
orange juice, motor vehicles and aircraft.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Brazilian government increased its 1998 budget
to finance exports to 1.5 billion dollars, 550 million dollars
more than that in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Industry, Commerce, and Tourism Jose Botafogo
Goncalves said the increased budget will help expand participation
of Brazilian firms in foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
