<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Museums Call for Tighter Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Museums and galleries in Italy must
apply sophisticated security equipment to fend off thieves, a
museum director said Thursday after three famous paintings were
stolen and six 17th Century paintings were damaged.
</P>
<P>
"If art becomes a question of mass interest, then security
systems need to be adapted," said Renato Nicolini, a respected
architect and director of Rome's Palazzo delle Esposizioni
said. "We need to use technology, not just guards."
</P>
<P>
Italy's artistic heritage has suffered two major blows in the
last two days.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday night, two Van Goghs and a Cezanne were stolen by
armed thieves from the capital's National Modern Art Gallery.
</P>
<P>
The next day six minor 17 Century paintings on display at the
Palazzo Venezia gallery were found to have small holes in them,
ranging from the size of a pinprick to the diameter of a drinking
straw. It resembled an act of vandalism in January, when three
paintings by Matisse on display at the Capitoline Museums were
punctured by pencil tips.
</P>
<P>
"We need to abandon our old-fashioned concepts of
security. What we need are security cameras, sophisticated
electronic surveillance systems, alarms and closed-circuit
televisions," said Nicolini. "An advanced network which will leave
a thief feeling like he's in a complicated Chinese box game from
which there is no escape."
</P>
<P>
He also questioned the recent decision of Deputy Premier and
Minister of Culture Walter Veltroni, who ordered a large number of
Italian museums to extend opening hours until 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally, I support the initiative because it is great for
art, but it is a decision which carries risks. It's obvious that
closing at 4 p.m. isn't as dangerous as closing at 10 p.m.," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
