<HEADLINE> Central American Atherosclerosis Congress Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Third Central American
Atherosclerosis Congress was inaugurated Thursday by Panamanian
President Ernesto Perez Balladares, with the attendance of
scientists from eight central American countries.
</P>
<P>
The three-day event here was organized by the Central American
Federation and the Panamanian Association for the Prevention and
Treatment of Atherosclerosis.
</P>
<P>
Noting that atherosclerosis is one of the major killers in the
developed countries, Francisco Iglesia, president of the
organizing committee, said it had also begun to affect people in
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Iglesia said the best way to prevent the disease is to help
people adopt healthy dietary habits.
</P>
<P>
Arterial hypertension, brain vessels disease and their
preventions are also on the agenda of the congress.
</P>
<P>
Doctors from Mexico, the United States, Colombia, Brazil,
Canada, Costa Rica, Spain and Panama are attending the meeting.
</P>
