<HEADLINE> Auctions Popular At Shanghai Universities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A Shanghai auctioneer sold a sheet
of souvenir "Hong Kong Returns to the Motherland" stamps for 100
yuan at a recent university auction held by Shanghai Finance and
Economics University, Fudan University, Tongji University, and
Shanghai Institute of Physical Culture.
</P>
<P>
Most of the auctioned items, like stamps, coins, toys, and
footballs with some local star's signature on them, came from
students who are close to graduation, the organizers say.
</P>
<P>
Half the proceeds of the auction will go to Project Hope,
China's largest program to aid poor pupils.
</P>
<P>
Many of Shanghai's university students are familiar with
auctions and some have invited well-known auctioneers to give
lectures. Shanghai's universities have organized other similar
activities like moot courts, and Shanghai University and Fudan
University have their own mini-stock exchange where students can
experiment with stock trading for as little as ten yuan.
</P>
<P>
"The auction has become a common thing in modern times, so it's
not unusual that university students know about it," says Lin
Yiping, the general manager of the Shanghai Auction House.
</P>
</TEXT>
