<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican FM Worried by FTAA Slowness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Foreign Minister
Roberto Rojas expressed his concern Thursday about the pace of
negotiations on the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four countries of the American continent took part in
negotiations for the creation of the biggest free trade area in
the world before the year 2005. The talks began at a regional
summit in Santiago, Chile, in April.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica has tried to advance more rapidly in the reduction
of tariffs and in the signing of bilateral free trade agreements.
It has an agreement with Mexico, in force since 1994, and expects
to sign another with Chile, with whom it has already signed a
framework agreement, said Rojas.
</P>
<P>
"The FTAA process goes too slowly," said Rojas. "We see
resistance from the United States and Mercosur (the Southern
Common Market made up by Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay)
countries."
</P>
<P>
He said some major U.S. sectors have criticized the results of
the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) signed by the
United States, Canada and Mexico. This made it more difficult to
gain support from the United States for the negotiation of the
FTAA.
</P>
<P>
In the same way, Mercosur seems more interested in
consolidating its own integration and was not willing to sacrifice
it for the FTAA, Rojas added.
</P>
<P>
"Our perception is that the FTAA will advance very slowly, and
for this we want to advance by our own account as fast as we can,"
said the Costa Rican foreign minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
