<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A friend In Need Is A Friend Indeed By Dong Xueqing and Liu Guangjun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Xingdi Electronics Co. Ltd., a
Korean electronics company in the city of Weihai in China's
Shandong Province, has been through some hard times in recent
months, because of the Asian financial crisis that has not spared
the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Employees had asked that their salaries be cut, in order to
deal with the situation, and made other cost cutting
proposals. These measures proved successful and orders continued
to arrive, and, as a result, the company's output was up 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
But, Xingdi was just one of many ROK-backed companies in this
province that survived the financial turmoil because of the moral
and financial assistance of local Chinese governments and people.
</P>
<P>
After being told these stories, Yong Youn Seok, the head of the
Commercial Section of the ROK Embassy in Beijing, commented
simply, "A friend in need is a friend indeed," but went on to say,
"As early as the 7th century, Koreans began commercial adventures
in the Shandong Peninsula, beginning the now centuries-old trade
ties with China."
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, ROK investors have made the Shandong
Peninsula their first choice because of the geographical and
cultural proximity, and Shandong is now home to at least 2,500
ROK-funded firms, involving 3.78 billion US dollars worth of
ROK funds. ROK is the second largest investor in China, and a
third of that investment is in Shandong.
</P>
<P>
"China has benefited from ROK investors," says one Foreign
Economic and Trade Ministry official, "and ROK investment has
contributed remarkably to increased employment opportunities, the
GDP, taxes, and exports in the country."
</P>
<P>
Wu Guanzheng, secretary of the Shandong Provincial Committee of
the Chinese Communist Party, says that ROK-funded firms are
currently having great troubles, but also says that ROK
investors as "our friends", so the province needs to keep the
faith and help them keep profits up to get over the difficulties.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, the provincial government has had a campaign
to help ROK-funded firms with favorable tax, land-use, and
customs policies, and for water and power supplies. In Wendeng,
for example, government officials even donated money to save some
struggling Korean companies, and in other small cities,
ROK-funded companies have been advised by local governments to
use more local materials to keep costs down.
</P>
<P>
The province's Vice-Governor Du Shicheng, who is responsible
for foreign economic and trade affairs, urges local people to make
every effort to help ROK-funded companies get through these
troubled times and to consider the long-term interests of Sino-ROK
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We Koreans have always seen the Chinese as brothers, and vice
versa," says the Korean embassy's Yong, "and I greatly appreciate
what they have done to help the ROK-funded companies." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Voices Concern Over Unsolicited NATO in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia said on Thursday that NATO
should not take any military action unless it gets permission from
the United Nation's Security Council, or the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Rakhmanin, a spokesman for the Russian Foreign
Ministry, made this remark at a time when the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization's military deployment in Albania appeared
possible.
</P>
<P>
Since last year's political crisis in Albania, NATO has sent a
number of experts there to help Albania's army and police,
Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
He said the border between Albania and Yugoslavia's Kosovo
province should be strictly closed to foil weapons smuggling and
the infiltration of militiamen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
