<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economic Powerhouse Improving Tourism Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province, an economic
powerhouse in China, has changed the practice of building
artificial scenic spots, and has turned to developing unique local
tourism resources.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou Marine Museum and the Hongkong Wildlife World are
its latest brainchildren. The former is reportedly the world's
largest inland marine museum, while the latter is the largest
of its kind in China.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou Business Tourist Walking Street is cited as
another example. It almost cost nothing to build, as it is in the
downtown area. However, the street is attracting an increasing number
of visitors, not only from abroad but also local urbanites.
</P>
<P>
Bicycle-based tourism, agricultural sightseeing along the Pearl
River Delta area, expedition tours, and expeditions specially
arranged for women are becoming increasingly popular.
</P>
<P>
The province made a hit in the 1980s when a miniature park,
called the Window of the World, was completed in Shenzhen. Other
places followed suit. As a result, huge amounts of money were
spent on artificial scenic spots, but didn't yield expected
returns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
