<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Water Consumption In Mid-21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- China's annual water consumption
midway through the 21st century is expected to be 700 billion
cubic meters, compared with 500 billion cu.m. now.
</P>
<P>
Water consumption will continue to grow along with economic
development, according to Liu Changming, of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, who was recently here for an international symposium on
water resources and management.
</P>
<P>
Liu says that people's ideas about the sustained development of
water resources are changing and conservation technology is
improving so China can slow the increase in water consumption
without retarding economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the United States, and many European countries have
managed to get water consumption growth down to zero. The United
States consumes 500 billion cubic meters of water annually, but
its GDP is ten times that of China.
</P>
<P>
Many water conservancy projects like the Three Gorges on the
Yangtze River and the Xiaolangdi on the Yellow River are under
construction, while the Chinese government is tightening water
pollution controls.
</P>
<P>
Liu says that water consumption is decreasing in some cities
and he believes that zero growth can be realized in China in 20 to
50 years. Water for agricultural use now accounts for 80 percent
of the country's total, and industrial and urban consumption, the
rest.
</P>
<P>
Liu adds that controlling pollution, recycling waste water,
saving water resources, and setting a reasonable price for water
are the keys to decreasing water consumption.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Rebels Cancel Peace Talks With Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) has canceled peace talks with the Philippine
government scheduled for this weekend, the local television
reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The MILF rebels said they prefer to negotiate with the incoming
administration which will assume office on June 30 this year,
Southern Command chief Maj. Gen. Joselin Nazareno was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Negotiators from the MILF and the government have reached an
agreement to shelve the scheduled talks to be held in Marawi City,
capital of Lanao del Sur in the southern Philippines, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to resume contacts only after June 30
when President Fidel Ramos steps down and transfers power to his
successor elected in the May 11 elections.
</P>
<P>
The MILF leadership has expressed concern over the apparent
winning presidential candidate Vice President Joseph Estrada, whom
they said could renegade on any accord signed before his
assumption of power, according to Nazareno.
</P>
<P>
The 12,000-strong MILF, which has fought for a separate Islamic
state for more than two decades, is currently the largest
anti-government force in the country.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF) which had already signed a peace treaty
with the government in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the government began low-level exploratory peace
talks in January 1997, but have so far failed to agree on the
agenda and the timetable for formal peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
