<HEADLINE> Beijing Launches Preparations Against Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has launched all-round
preparations against this year's floods to protect the safety of
the Chinese capital, according to a deputy mayor of the city.
</P>
<P>
Yue Fuhong said that flood-control headquarters at the
municipal and county levels have been established, and the work in
this regard has been set as a criterion for judging the
performance of government officials.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is located in the northern part of the North China
Plain, a place vulnerable to natural disasters such as floods and
drought.
</P>
<P>
According to historical records, the city was hit by natural
disasters 794 times during the 580 years before 1949, 387 times by
floods.
</P>
<P>
The 680-km Yongding River is the major source of floods which
threaten Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Ministry of Water Resources warned that
Beijing should make better preparations against serious floods
this year, due to reports of unusual meteorological conditions
recently.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua has learned that since this spring, Beijing's investment
in water conservation has increased by 26 percent, with over 20
projects including dredging of rivers, improving the safety of
reservoirs, and reinforcing dykes and dams, completed.
</P>
<P>
The city's flood-control wireless telecommunications system and
a system for remote monitoring of the rainfall situation are in
operation and are in good condition.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Beijing has prepared flood-relief materials,
including 2.5 million straw bags, 12,000 cu m of timber, 11,000
vehicles and over 200 lifeboats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
