<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Posts Current Account Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines posted a current
account surplus of 68 million U.S. dollars for the first two
months of the year, a big improvement from the 45-million dollar
deficit during the same period last year, the Philippine newspaper
Malaya reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson was quoted as saying
Thursday the surplus was due to the narrowing trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that the current account surplus resulted in a
higher balance of payments surplus of 482 million dollars in the
first two months of this year from the year-ago level of 370
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Singson also expected the country to end the year with a
current account surplus after suffering over a decade of yearly
deficits.
</P>
<P>
Current account is made up of visible trade such as merchandise
exports and imports, and invisible trade referring to the income
and expenditure for banking, insurance, tourism and shipping
services together with profits earned overseas and interest
payments.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that the current account surplus would further
boost investors' confidence in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign fund managers always look at you CA (current
account) position rather than the balance of payments since it
(CA) is not dependent on capital inflows," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
