<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Lifts Tuna Embargo on Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States government on
Thursday lifted the tuna embargo imposed on Panama since 1991,
Commerce and Industry Minister Raul Hernandez announced.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the measure, which will enable Panama to
resume export of tuna to the United States, represents for the
Panamanian tuna industry a possibility of earning 150 million
U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
He added that Panama accepted all the guidelines imposed by the
United States for the lifting of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the two countries signed Thursday in
Washington the agreement on the program for the conservation of
the dolphin, ending the embargo which also affected since May of
1991 Costa Rica, Japan, Italy, Venezuela, Colombia, Honduras and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
"All the Panamanian fishing fleets belonging to the tuna
industry will be maintained according to the international
regulations," said Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
Hernandez said Panama will follow closely the maritime rules
for the protection of the dolphins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
