<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Men Win Hockey World Cup Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Olympic gold medalists and hosts
the Netherlands opened its bid to add the world trophy to its
credit as well on Thursday at the 1998 World Cup Field Hockey
Tournament, beating Canada 3-1 in Utrecht.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch side, runners-up at the last cup outing in Sydney
four years ago, did not hesitate in demonstrating its ambition in
the game that it dominated with deft dribbling and passing.
</P>
<P>
Only scoring needed polish to secure a better placing of the
round-robin group tourney that already avoided the hosts early
clashes with either World Cup holders Pakistan or Olympic silver
medalists Spain and bronze medalists Australia.
</P>
<P>
Germany and India, fourth and fifth at the Sydney World Cup,
were pooled with the Netherlands in group A.
</P>
<P>
In the other men's group, both Australia and Pakistan won
handsomely, trouncing Poland 8-0 and routing Malaysia 7-2
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Like its opener a day earlier, the Dutch women had to come from
behind to win its Thursday's game against England.
</P>
<P>
The English women, who beat India in the previous rounder,
first led 1-0. But the host team would not let go the home
advantage and plowed ferotiously back by scoring two of their
three goals deep into the second half of the 70-minute game.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch women now lead group B on more goals scored, followed
by Argentina. The clash between the two teams slated for next
Wednesday is likely to turn out the decider for the top place of
the six-team group preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
Group winner takes up the second-place finisher of the other
group in the sudden-death semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Olympic runners-up South Korea pulled back one game by
squeezing past New Zealand five goals to four in women's action.
The South Koreans went 2-1 down to Argentina on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
