<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Government Rebutts Accusation on Technology Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. State Department
official rebutted here Thursday the accusation that the Clinton
Administration had allowed sensitive technology transfer to China,
defending the cooperation with that Asian country in satellite
launch.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman James Rubin told a noon press briefing that the
charges were based on "incorrect information." He hoped the fact
would turn out as it is before the American people some time.
</P>
<P>
"The whole underlying suggestion that somehow we want to
transfer technology to the Chinese, as a result of I don't know
what, is simply fatuous, and the more rational analysis...would
certainly help bring to the American people an understanding that
this process does not transfer technology by design," he said.
</P>
<P>
Critics in Republican-dominant Congress put their fingers at
President Bill Clinton for allowing two American companies to
launch commercial satellites atop Chinese rockets. The House of
Representative and Senate have both set up panels to look into the
allegations that missile guidance technology was leaked to the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The companies, the Hughes Electronics Corporation and Loral,
have both denied any wrongdoing, while the Administration asserts
foolproof has been in place to protect American technology.
</P>
<P>
"What we are trying to communicate to all of you is that for
three administrations in a row, we have been weighing the costs
and benefits of those risks and pursuing the exact same policy for
three administrations," Rubin stressed.
</P>
<P>
The denial and assertion have so far failed to convince the
congressmen who obviously wanted to make it a big issue before
President Clinton goes to visit China in June. The House of
Representatives voted Wednesday to curb satellite and
high-technology exports to China. The Senate was also expected to
vote over the legislation next month.
</P>
<P>
"We were extremely disappointed by this vote in the House of
representatives. If passed in the Senate, this legislation will
threaten American leadership in the commercial satellite business,
and therefore, threaten an area where America has a competitive
advantage," the spokesman warned.
</P>
<P>
According to The Wall Street Journal Thursday, the harsh
measures, if applied, will cost U.S. aerospace companies hundreds
of million dollars and open a window for foreign corporations to
jump ahead in the competition to provide global-communications
services.
</P>
<P>
Sharing the anxiety, Rubin said that the misfunctioning of a
communications satellite in the last two days have made the people
understand better why it is important for the Chinese to launch
American satellites.
</P>
<P>
"As everyone saw so graphically yesterday, the absence of
sufficient satellite capacity and the absence of backup satellites
and material effect on not only the lives of Americans but our
competitive advantage in this area," he said, with a reference to
the vast breakdown of communications since Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal reported that the U.S. government
projections are that satellite makers' demand will outstrip
commercial launches for the next 10 years. Last year, Chinese,
France, U.S. and Russian rockets sent 35 commercial satellites
aloft. But as many as 350 satellites could be vying for space on
launch vehicles in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
"If they (American satellites) can't get off into space, we are
worse off. There is a risk in not letting them do that," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
However, he denied any linkage between the government's policy
and fund-raising drive in the 1996 presidential election campaign.
There were allegations that the Loral chief executive officer
donated a lot of money to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
"Well, you're inventing a linkage that is simply no evidence
for it," Rubin replied to a question asked at the press briefing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
