<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Satellite Failure Affects Life of Americans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of thousands of pagers
carried by Americans have been silent since Tuesday evening as a
major U.S. owned satellite suffered a computer failure and moved
out of position.
</P>
<P>
At least eight of the nation's 10 biggest paging companies
depend on the PanAmSat's Galaxy IV satellite were unable to supply
service to millions of hospitals, police departments and other
business and individual customers.
</P>
<P>
National Public Radio broadcasts and some small TV operations
were disrupted. Drivers at Chevron gas stations could not use
pumps at thousands of service stations.
</P>
<P>
Wireless telecommunications services of some major chain stores
were also down for hours.
</P>
<P>
PanAmSat, which is mainly owned by the Hughes Electronics Corp.
subsidiary of General Motors Corp., was trying hard to fix the
problem. But it was reported that it may take several days before
the nation's paging network is fully restored, and as long as a
week for a backup for broadcasting to be put in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980522.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldova's New Cabinet Validated by Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The parliament of Moldova
validated on Thursday the new cabinet led by Ion Ciubuc and it's
work program, reported the Messenger, the Moldovan National TV
Station.
</P>
<P>
Thursday was the deadline, according to the constitution, when
the premier designated had to ask a confidence vote to his team.
</P>
<P>
A compromise was reached regarding the cabinet formation,
between Ion Ciubuc and the "Alliance for democracy and reforms",
the governing coalition just a few hours before the voting.
Earlier, the Democratic Convention of Moldova threatened to vote
against any cabinet whose head ignores its proposals.
</P>
<P>
The principal problem on the constitution of the new cabinet
was the Ciubuc's insistence to maintain Nicolae Cernomaz as
minister of state and Mihai Plamadeala as minister of interior. At
last, Nicolae Cernomaz remained in the cabinet, while Mihai
Plamadeala had to leave.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet pledged that the stability of the national
currency (lei) exchange rate in relation to the U.S. dollar will
be maintained and that the inflation by 2001 will not exceed 8
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
