<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sets Conditions for Resuming IMF Aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States will see
whether proper conditions are created in Indonesia for Washington
to support a resumption of disbursements to Indonesia under a 43
billion U.S. dollars International Monetary Fund rescue package,
The State Department said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, told reporters
that the United States wants to see a series of principles to be
followed by Indonesia's new leader Jusuf Habibie before it could
consider the possibility of resumption of IMF aid to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Habibie sworn in as Indonesia's president on Thursday after
Suharto announced his decision to resign on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said three principles -- inclusiveness, dialogue and
democracy -- should be followed in the post-Suharto era.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the United
States would consult with other countries about whether the
International Monetary Fund should renew the rescue package to
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
A senior IMF official said on Wednesday before Suharto
decided to resign that it was suspending disbursements to
Indonesia and may have to drastically overhaul the program.
</P>
<P>
Stanley Fischer, first deputy IMF managing director,
confirmed that civil unrest will delay the previously planned
disbursement of 1 billion U.S. dollars on June 4.
</P>
<P>
Fischer stressed that given the steep decline in the value of
the rupiah, Indonesia's currency, and its impact on economic
assumptions and targets in the IMF program, it is very likely
the terms will have to be renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said on Thursday a
resumption of IMF ties with Indonesia depended on Indonesia's
willingness to pursue economic and political reforms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
