<HEADLINE> Two Bodies Found at Student Shooter's Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Two people were found dead in
the home of the student who opened fire with a semiautomatic rifle
in an Oregon high school that killed at least one person and
wounded 24 others on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two bodies of a man and a women were found by police an
hour and a half after the shooting by a boy who was expelled a day
earlier for trying to bring a gun to school. But the relationship
of the victims were unknown.
</P>
<P>
The 15-year-old student, dressed in a cream-colored trench
coat, started the shooting just before 8:00 a.m. in a cafeteria at
Thurston High School in Springfield, Oregon. He run through the
cafeteria, where up to 400 people were gathered, firing his rifle
from the hip. Among the wounded, seven were in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
A wrestling student, despite being shot himself, tackled the
shooter, got the gun away from him and held him down. The suspect
was arrested about 20 minutes after the shooting broke out.
</P>
<P>
Students in the school said that the shooter had always said
that it would be fun to kill someone. One day before the shooting,
he told a couple of people that he was probably going to do
something stupid Thursday and get back at the people who had
expelled him.
</P>
<P>
The school of 1,350 students was shut down immediately after
the shooting and parents, many of them weeping and screaming,
waited outside. A school official read the names of students who
were injured.
</P>
<P>
Learning the event, U.S. President Bill Clinton expressed the
nation's sympathy to the victims and their families.
</P>
<P>
"I know that all Americans are heartbroken," Clinton said
during a Rose Garden ceremony on NATO expansion. "Our thoughts and
prayers are with the families of the people who were killed and
wounded, and with that entire fine community."
</P>
<P>
The president also called the school's principal to express
personal condolences, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
It was the latest in a series of school shootings across the
country. On the same day, a 15-year-old boy carrying a gun got on
his school bus in Onalaska, Washington, took his girl friend off
and then went to his home and shot himself in the head as her
father tried to break down the door.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a high school student shot and killed a student in
a school parking lot in Fayetteville Tennessee, three days before
they were to graduate, apparently because they had argued about a
girl.
</P>
<P>
On April 24, a 14-year-old boy opened fire at an eighth-grade
graduation dance in Edinboro, Pennsylvania, killing a teacher and
wounding two students and another teacher.
</P>
<P>
On March 24, an 11-year-old boy and his 13-year-old friend
opened fire on classmates in Jonesboro, Arkansas, killing four
pupils and a teacher and wounded 10 others.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, a 16-year-old student in Pearl, Mississippi,
killed his mother, then went to school and shot nine students. Two
of them died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
